<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Plans to Charge Car Parking to Cut Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 20 (Reuters) - British Deputy Prime Minister John
Prescott Monday unveiled a white paper for transforming the
nation's transport system, with plans for charges on car users to
finance the improvements.
</P>
<P>
Prescott told parliament he would grant new powers to local
councils to charge car drivers for using congested roads and for
work-place parking. The cash raised will be ring-fenced for
spending on the public transport system.
</P>
<P>
In what he described as "a new deal for motorists" to cut
traffic congestion and pollution, the government will give new
powers to the Highways Agency to pilot road charging schemes and
use the income to reinvest in the road network.
</P>
<P>
He also spelt out a range of measures to encourage freight on
to railways, including proposals to use the proceeds from the
planned part-sale of the National Air Traffic Control Service to
reinvest in other transport projects.
</P>
<P>
These include proposals for Euro-gauge freight rail system
running from the Anglo-French Channel Tunnel through to Scotland,
if terms can be agreed, Prescott said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
