<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Tour Northeastern China's Biggest River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, July 20 (Xinhua) -- A group of people recently began
a journey along the Songhua River, China's third biggest river,
thanks to a company in Harbin, the capital of Heilongjiang
Province.
</P>
<P>
The river runs for 1,745 kilometers from the Changbai mountains
in Jilin Province into the Heilongjiang River. Chinese began to
live in the Songhua river valley as early as 3,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The group will study the River's water quality and the ecology
along it, explains Qiu Shiyu, chairman of the board of a jade
company that is sponsoring the activity and a participant.
</P>
<P>
The group is made up of entrepreneurs, an artist and a
technician. They began their trip from Tianchi Lake in the
Changbai mountains and went to Tongjiangkou on the Russian border,
where the Songhua river meets the Heilongjiang river.
</P>
<P>
The tour is expected to last 40 days, and cover 1,840
kilometers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
