<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-20 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Electricity Employees Stage Strike For </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Lebanese employees in
the state-run electricity company staged a 24-hour strike on
Monday in protest against the company administration's failure to
meet their demands on benefits and working conditions.
</P>
<P>
"Electricity will be supplied as normal but in the event of a
network failure, we will not carry out repairs until the strike is
over," Abdel-Ghani Abla, the head of Electricite du Liban(EDL)'s
union, told the Voice of the People radio.
</P>
<P>
The union leader also threatened an open-ended strike if the
government and EDL's board failed to act before the union's
deadline, now set for the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
"We sent memorandums to administration officials a month and a
half ago explaining our case but we never received a response," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The union will meet on Wednesday with Electricity and Water
Resources Minister Elie Hobeika to brief him on their demands
prior to a cabinet session scheduled for later in the day, in
which he is expected to raise the issue.
</P>
<P>
The workers are asking for a 30 percent increase in financial
aid for their children's school fees, a demand that has been
rejected by the finance ministry.
</P>
<P>
They are also calling for a new ranks and salaries scale, based
on a study of the issue drafted by the union.
</P>
<P>
The union wants to increase the minimum bonuses awarded for
those working under hazardous conditions to 300,000 Lebanese
pounds (about 200 U.S. dollars) a month from the current 118,000
pounds (about 79 dollars).
</P>
<P>
To support EDL employees, workers from other sectors like
tobacco, telephone, and the public transport also carried out a
one hour strike Monday.
</P>
<P>
Electricity workers last held a strike last October, after
which two of their demands were met. 
</P>
</TEXT>
