<HEADLINE> Strike by Zimbabwe's Trade Union Not Ruled Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Congress of Trade
Unions (ZCTU) Monday said it still had the option to call for
another nationwide work boycott, denying the reports that it had
reached an understanding with the government.
</P>
<P>
ZCTU Secretary-General Morgan Tsvangirai told the Zimbabwe
News Agency that a final decision would be reached at the General
Council's meeting which would be held in Mutare of east Zimbabwe
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"How can we rule out the mass job stayaway when we have not
even met and even without the knowledge of the people we
represent?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
The ZCTU organized a mass job stayaway in January which
crippled the country's economy resulting in the loss of business
worth more than 3.8 million U.S. Dollars over two days.
</P>
<P>
ZCTU has demanded among others crapping the five percent
development levy, tax on pensions and the need for the government
to find a long term solution to increases of basic commodities.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether a nationwide stayaway was still the only option
for the ZCTU to force the government into accepting some of its
demands, Tsvangiral said, "We are not ruling out the stayaway but
we still have to discuss all available options." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
