<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Little Progress Made in Indian-U.S. Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Little progress was made Monday
in the third round of talks between India and the United States
with India ruling out any roll back of its nuclear weaponization
and missile programs.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from his meeting with Indian Prime Atal Bihari
Vajpayee here Monday afternoon, visiting U.S. Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott told reporters that the discussions were held
in an atmosphere and spirit of quiet diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
"We have more work ahead of us....I would rather wait until we
reach a point that is conclusive. We are not there yet and we have
a long way to go," said Talbott who arrived in the Indian capital
Sunday evening amidst tight security.
</P>
<P>
He said that he conveyed Washington's desire to put bilateral
relations on a solid footing in the aftermath of India's nuclear
tests.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that President Bill Clinton's visit to India
slated for November this year was under review.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) reported that Talbott delivered
a letter from President Clinton to Vajpayee, the content of which
is unknown.
</P>
<P>
Talbott is the first high-ranking U.S. official to visit the
South Asian country since India conducted nuclear tests in May.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Talbott held a one-hour meeting with Vajpayee's
special envoy Jaswant Singh who said that India would not
compromise on its security interests.
</P>
<P>
Both Talbott and Singh termed their talks as constructive and
continuing and said they exchanged views on strategic perspectives
of regional and international developments.
</P>
<P>
Talbott said the talks between the two sides covered a wide
range of security issues relating to arms control, disarmament,
non-proliferation and regional and international developments.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of External Affairs issued a statement Monday
afternoon, saying that Talbott's talks with Indian officials were
marked by a spirit of working together to find common ground and
to narrow gaps in their governments' respective perceptions.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Vajpayee was informed of the progress
made during the talks towards removal of problems in Indo-U.S.
relations which surfaced after India's nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
"There is now a clearer understanding of each other's concerns
and certain steps in the direction of addressing those concerns
are contemplated," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
However, it added, (some) ground remained to be covered and it
had been agreed that another round of talks between Talbott and
Singh would be held in the second half of August in Washington.
</P>
<P>
This is the third meeting between Talbott and Singh in less
than 40 days. His first two rounds of talks with Singh -- in
Washington on June 12 and in Frankfurt on July 9 -- reached no
concrete results with New Delhi asserting that its demand for
building a nuclear deterrent was not negotiable.
</P>
<P>
It is significant that the talks come ten days before the
planned crucial meeting between Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee and Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif on the
sidelines of the three-day summit of the South Asian Association
for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) in Colombo beginning on July 29.
</P>
<P>
India had also made it clear that it would not sign the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) in its present form while
Washington insisted on the immediate and unconditional signing of
the CTBT by India and refraining from deploying nuclear weapons or
advanced missile systems in the country.
</P>
<P>
Talbott and Singh are scheduled to have another round of talks
Tuesday morning before the U.S. delegation leaves for Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
Both the U.S. and India were reportedly keen on improving the
bilateral relations so as to save the plans of President Bill
Clinton to visit South Asian countries later this year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation included Deputy Assistant Secretary for
Non-Proliferation Robert Einhorn, senior adviser in the National
Security Council Bruce Riedel, Vice Chairman of the Joint Chiefs
of Staff Joseph Ralston, Assistant Secretary of State for South
Asian Affairs Karl Inderfurth and U.S. Ambassador to India Richard
Celeste. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
