<HEADLINE> Mandela Reiterates Support for Angolan Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela reiterated Monday his government's support for the
Angolan peace process which is now facing a crisis.
</P>
<P>
Mandela made the remarks during his short stay here on the way
to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
He said Angolan peace process is now facing the worst crisis
in four years due to the failure of opposition National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) in implementing the
Lusaka Peace Accord. Instead, the former rebel movement has been
snatching back some cities and towns from government control.
</P>
<P>
Mandela pledged that the South African government will
continue to support the Angolan Peace Process.
</P>
<P>
Under the current circumstances, he said, the Angolan
government should fight for every inch of land. Meanwhile, he
urged the Angolan people to work hard to achieve the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is the first leg of Mandela's south American tour which
will also bring him to Argentine to attend the summit of Mercado
Commun del Sur (Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
Reports from the Angola News Agency said UNITA has launched
armed attacks in several provinces in Angola.
</P>
<P>
In the diamond-rich Lunda-Norte Province in northeast Angola,
the national police clashed with UNITA militiamen. However, the
police had taken control over the situation, with UNITA forces
fleeing toward the area bordering the Democratic Republic of
Congo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
