<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prisons' Budget Soars in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The cost of maintaining prisons in
Zimbabwe has doubled over the past four years to 454 million
Zimbabwean Dollars (26 million U.S. Dollars) this year although
the prison population has remained stable.
</P>
<P>
"As indicated by the figures, the costs are definitely
increasing. The major causes of the increasing costs are mainly
due to the inflation and the economic environment," a spokesman
for the Zimbabwe Prison Service told the Herald daily at the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, Zimbabwe's prisons, meant to hold
about 16,000 inmates, hold about 22,000. However, he said, the
number of inmates has stabilized over the past four years.
</P>
<P>
"From the figures of the past four years, it is quite evident
that the total number of inmates in the country has been stable.
However, this is well above the current holding capacity of
16,000 inmates," he said.
</P>
<P>
Prisons' expenditure has encompassed provision of food,
clothing, bedding, medication for the criminals and officers'
salaries and wages.
</P>
<P>
James Devitte, a high court judge, said that Zimbabwe faced
the prospect of a high prison population as present economic
difficulties meant that an increasing number of people would have
difficulties in sustaining themselves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
