<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-20 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Vows to Protect Turkish Cypriots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
reaffirmed Monday that Turkey will carry out its promise to defend
the freedom and rights of Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
In a congratulatory letter to Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash on the 24th anniversary of Turkey's military intervention
in Cyprus, Demirel said that Turkey will retaliate if the Turkish
Cypriot community is in danger, the semi-official Anatolia News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The Turkish Cypriot people should be at ease. Turkey is
carefully evaluating those provocative developments within the
framework of her past experience and shall take all necessary
measures," he said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of
the small island on July 20, 1974 when Greek Cypriot military
officers attempted to seek union with Greece. The island is now
divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south and Turkish
Cypriot-controlled north.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the operation, Demirel said that it ended
"pressure, violence and pain upon the Turkish Cypriot people" and
created the conditions which were necessary for permanent peace in
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared in 1983 "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" which was recognized only by
Ankara. At present, 35,000-strong Turkish troops are stationed
there to keep a deterrent on the Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish president stated that Turkey will do what it can to
help Turkish Cypriots gain a more prosperous future, saying the
Cyprus peace process is of great significance to peace and
stability of the eastern Mediterranean region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he accused "some circles" of continuing their
activities to provoke tension on the divided island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed a deal with Russia early last year to buy S-300
surface-to-air missiles in a bid to boost defense, prompting harsh
reaction from Turkey and Turkish Cypriots, which have vowed to
take all necessary steps to prevent the missile deployment.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz, accompanied by a group of
civilian and military officials, flew to northern Cyprus to
participate in the July 20 celebrations and show Ankara's
determination to protect Turkish Cypriots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
