<HEADLINE> Cypriot FM Warns Foreign Observers of Losing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides Monday warned foreign observers in Cyprus of losing
credibility if they fail to react to the recent visits of Turkish
warplanes and naval vessels to northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after attending a church service to
commemorate those killed during the 1974 Turkish invasion of
Cyprus, Kasoulides said these visits were "illegal" and he would
like to see reactions from the observers.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said 12 Turkish military planes, four naval
vessels and two submarines arrived in the Turkish Cypriot
controlled northern Cyprus over the weekend to participate in the
celebration to mark the 24th anniversary of Turkish troops'
landing on the island.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Cypriot government came under fire for
allowing Greek fighter planes to land on its newly-built air base
in western part of the island, a move to which Turkey responded
by sending six warplanes to the north.
</P>
<P>
"The question to all those foreigners, who rushed to express
concern about the arrival of the Greek planes, is whether they can
convince us that this time they are acting as honest brokers
through their response to Turkey's provocative actions,"
Kasoulides said.
</P>
<P>
If they ignored the Turkish actions, he added, they would lose
all credibility as "objective observers."
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides said the Cypriot government would make all
appropriate representations to the United Nations over Turkey's
"provocative actions".
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
