<HEADLINE> Greece Blasts Turkish PM's Visit to Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Greece Monday condemned the visit
by Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz to northern Cyprus, calling it
another act of provocation by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The attack was launched here by visiting Greek Interior
Minister Alecos Papadopoulos following his meeting with Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that Yilmaz's visit was "nothing else but
another link to the endless chain of Turkish provocations".
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz arrived in the Turkish Cypriot-controlled northern
Cyprus earlier Monday to attend celebrations on the 24th
anniversary of the Turkish military intervention on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Papadopoulos was in Cyprus representing the Greek
government to attend the events to mark the anniversary of what
they called Turkey's invasion of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since Turkey landed its troops and
took over the northern third of Cyprus on July 20, 1974, after a
coup launched by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has since maintained some 35,000 troops in the north
with the claimed aim of protecting the Turkish Cypriot minority.
</P>
<P>
Papadopoulos said during their meeting, President Clerides
briefed him on the latest developments in the situation concerning
the island.
</P>
<P>
The Greek minister pledged that both Greece and Cyprus would
continue their joint efforts in seeking a peaceful solution to the
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Cyprus signed a joint defense pact in November
1993, under which Greece will come to aid in case Cyprus is
attacked.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz's visit came at a time when tensions on the island have
escalated since early last year when Cyprus ordered a Russian
anti-aircraft missile system.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has threatened to strike the missiles if they are
deployed, but Cyprus has said that it would not cancel the missile
plan unless progress is made in resuming the stalled peace talks
and on its proposal for demilitarizing the island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
