<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Green Lines Restored in Somali Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 20 (Xinhua) -- People in the Somali capital
were terrified Monday by the sudden restoration of the former
green lines which had disgracefully divided Mogadishu in the past
seven years.
</P>
<P>
The four main junctions linking the two sides of the capital
have been stormed by heavily armed infantry militiamen using
several battle wagons.
</P>
<P>
The militiamen who did not fire at anybody have forcefully
blocked all kinds of transport vehicles, public or private, from
crossing the green lines at about 9:00 am local time Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, the movement of the pedestrians is not yet restricted
as hundreds of people have gone on foot to either side of the
capital for their normal duties.
</P>
<P>
The uncertainty created by the new blockade has immediately
hindered major business activities within the capital as the
movement of large amounts of money to any side of Mogadishu
became almost impossible or highly dangerous.
</P>
<P>
Without giving any specific reason, the militiamen manning the
green lines have ordered all public transport buses not to try to
come close to them.
</P>
<P>
"This is the order we have," said one of them with an AK-47
assault rifle.
</P>
<P>
According to sources close to the main faction leaders of the
Somali capital, the restoration of the green lines has a
political motive prompted by what they characterized as minor
political difference that emerged between the peace brokers of
Mogadishu and other politicians after serious negotiations Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
The politicians did not rule out the possibility of an
agreement very soon. However, they declined to mention who is
responsible.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the people Monday pointed their finger of blame
on Hussein Hajji Bod, one of Ali Mahdi's deputy chairmen, who has
been a rival of Ali Mahdi himself ever since the Cairo peace deal
was reached late last December.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Hajji Bod who spoke with Xinhua Monday has shouldered
the responsibility of the militiamen who were dispatched for
sealing off the green lines.
</P>
<P>
The militiamen were sent merely to secure public order and
combat the lawlessness as part of what he called a peace
campaign.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to correct if anything went wrong during these
operations and we did not order the militiamen to stop the
buses," said Bod.
</P>
<P>
This unforeseen closure of the former green lines came at a
time when there is an air of optimism for the settlement of
Mogadishu political crises following the peace agreement between
Ali Mahdi Mohamed, Hussein Mohamed Aidid and Osman Ali Atto on
one hand and one of Ali Mahdi's deputy chairmen on the other.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi's deputy chairman, the well-known militia leader
Muse Sudi Yalahow, has been offered the post of a deputy
co-chairmen in Mogadishu's forthcoming administration. Ali Mahdi
has five deputy chairmen in his faction.
</P>
<P>
The green lines had also been restored at a time when the
people of the capital had been expecting the announcement of the
inauguration of Mogadishu's air and seaport late Monday.
</P>
<P>
The air and seaport of the capital had been out of use since
1995, just a few months after the departure of the multi-national
forces of the United Nations from Mogadishu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0026 </DOCNO>
