<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends UNOMIG Mandate Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 20 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Monday recommended extension of the mandate of the United
Nations Observer Mission in Georgia (UNOMIG) for a further period
of six months until January 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council, Annan said the situation
on the ground remains tense and the risk of new confrontation is
high, and both the Georgian authorities and the Abkhaz authorities
lack willingness to renounce violence and seriously consider
peaceful options for the resolution of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the UNOMIG's ability to operate smoothly has been
further hampered by the danger and security threats to the mission
personnel.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said its presence in the country is essential.
Not only does the mission's presence continue to be a stability
factor in the area and to provide useful support for the political
process, but it also helps to create a sense of confidence and
security among the local population of the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
Annan condemned the attacks against peacekeepers of the United
Nations and the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) and urged
the Georgian authorities, especially the Abkhaz authorities, to
take measures to ensure the safety and security of the personnel
of the UNOMIG and the CIS. 
