<HEADLINE> Shevardnadze Urges Speedy Probe Into Murder of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Georgian President Eduard
Shevardnadze has ordered law enforcement agencies to quickly find
out those who murdered a U.N. worker and bring them to justice,
saying it was "a matter of national dignity."
</P>
<P>
Maria Wewiorska, a 31-year-old Polish women working for the
U.N. military observer mission, was murdered in her apartment last
Tuesday in Tbilisi, the Georgian capital.
</P>
<P>
"The timely investigation of the murder... is a matter of
national dignity for Georgia," the Itar-Tass quoted Shevardnadze
as saying over the national radio.
</P>
<P>
He said authorities had acquired "a lot of information" about
the circumstances of the crime.
</P>
<P>
A Georgian investigator in charge of the probe said Wewiorska
might have been killed by a robber.
</P>
<P>
The country's Foreign Ministry hoped that the incident would
not prevent the mission of the United Nations and other
international organizations from continuing their operation in
Georgia in search of a peaceful settlement to the Abkhazia
conflict.
</P>
<P>
A bloody interethnic unrest escalated into a violent armed
conflict in 1992 when Georgian government troops were dispatched
to the breakaway republic. About 7,000 people died in the conflict
before a cease-fire agreement was reached in May 1994 under
Russian auspices. Sporadic violence, however, persisted.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council condemned Wewiorska's murder and
reminded the two conflicting sides in Georgia of their obligation
to protect the life and ensure the security of the U.N. observer
mission in Georgia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
