<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Says Agreement Depends on Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said Monday that if Palestinian negotiators hold serious
talks with Israel, an agreement on the second redeployment would
be wrapped up soon.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the remarks just a day after the resumption of
the direct Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, which have been
stalled for months over the extent of next Israeli troop pullback
in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with visiting Estonian Foreign Minister Toomas Ilves
here, Netanyahu said it was still too early to say if the
Palestinian negotiators have come with a mandate to reach an
agreement, adding that "we will know it in coming days."
</P>
<P>
"If they have, the talks can be wrapped up in the near future,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) deputy head Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) met
Sunday in Tel Aviv in an effort to reach an agreement on the
long overdue second redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The talks came at the urging of the United States, which
called on the two sides to negotiate directly to resolve
differences over a U.S. initiative calling for Israel to withdraw
from another 13 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Among the key issues discussed were the nature of the 13
percent withdrawal, revision of the clauses in the Palestinian
Covenant calling for Israel's destruction and amendment of the
U.S.-brokered security memorandum initiated last December.
</P>
<P>
On the redeployment, Israel reportedly demanded placing special
restrictions on 3 percent of the 13 percent of West Bank to be
yielded to the Palestinians. In the area, Israeli troops have the
right to reenter in case of need and the Palestinians residents
are not allowed to build without Israeli permits.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai and Mazen have agreed to set up several teams to
continue the negotiations in order to clinch a deal on all the
issues.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai, a moderate among the right-wing Israeli coalition,
has said that he hoped his meeting with Abu Mazen would lead to
a summit between Netanyahu and the PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat to
finalize a deal on the second redeployment.
</P>
<P>
And Netanyahu also repeated his willingness on Monday to hold
a meeting with Arafat. But the Palestinian leader has rejected to
meet Netanyahu unless he comes with real determination to move
forward the peace process that has been stalled for 16 months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
