<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Ready to Help Papua New Guinea in Disaster Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations stands
ready to help Papua New Guinea in overcoming the damage brought up
by last week's tidal wave, Secretary-General Kofi Annan said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued through his spokesman, Annan said he was
profoundly distressed to learn of the terrible damage, especially
by the "tragic loss of so many lives, including those of hundreds
if not thousands of children."
</P>
<P>
He said the U.N. will help assess the damage and mobilize the
necessary international relief effort. The U.N. Office for the
Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs in Geneva is leading the
relief effort, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
An undersea quake with the magnitude of 7.0 on the Richter
scale was registered near the Northern coast of Papua New Guinea
Friday, which triggered a tidal wave of some 10 meters, crashing
into a coastal area stretching 30 km. The affected area is 800 km
north of the capital Port Moresby.
</P>
<P>
At least seven villages have been wiped out and destroyed. The
latest information received from the U.N. Development Program
(UNDP) Office in Port Moresby put the official number of deaths at
725.
</P>
<P>
However, the death toll is expected to rise considerably as a
large number of people are still unaccounted for. In addition,
hundreds of people have been injured. A state of national disaster
has been declared in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
