<HEADLINE> German Businessman Gets Jail Term for Nuke Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 20 (Xinhua) -- A German court Monday sentenced a
German businessman to three years and nine months in prison on
charges of illegally selling machinery parts to Pakistan that are
used to enrich uranium.
</P>
<P>
The 67-year-old businessman was found guilty of violating
German laws to control exports of military goods by delivering to
Pakistan from 1988 to 1993 accessories for gas centrifuges used to
enrich weapons-grade uranium for the country's nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
The exports had endangered German foreign relations and
undermined the German policy of non-proliferation of mass
destruction weapons, the Stuttgart court said.
</P>
<P>
The businessman denied the accusations at the start of the
trial in March. But after Pakistan's nuclear tests in May, he
admitted that he could not rule out the possibility that his
products could also be used for nuclear purpose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
