<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kok Appointed Chief to Form Dutch Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Dutch Queen Beatrix Wilhelmina
Armgard Monday appointed outgoing Prime Minister Wim Kok the chief
for the formation of the next coalition government.
</P>
<P>
This was announced in the Hague after the queen met with the
three informateurs or persons in charge of pre-cabinet formation
negotiations, according to news reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The appointment meant that Kok is the prime minister-designate
of the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Kok, Frits Bolkestein and Els Borst, the three informateurs,
represent the Labor Party, the People's Party for Freedom and
Democracy and the Democrats 66.
</P>
<P>
The three parties had formed the previous coalition for a term
of four years during which the coalition won the trust of the
Dutch public.
</P>
<P>
In the May elections, the Labor Party won 45 seats; the
People's Party for Freedom and Democracy got 38 seats, and the
Democrats 66 had 14 seats.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition, the Christian Democratic Appeal, took 29
seats.
</P>
<P>
The trio combined accounts for 97 of the 150 seats in the lower
house of the Dutch parliament.
</P>
<P>
Kok is expected to spend the next few days selecting candidates
for his cabinet and the queen will finally confirm Kok's choice in
office.
</P>
<P>
Several of the previous coalition, however, have announced
their wish not to form part of the new coalition. They include
former Foreign Minister Hans van Mierlo, Justice Minister Winnie
Sorgdrager, Education Minister Jo Ritzen, Economy Minister Hans
Wijers and Social Affairs Minister Ad Melkert.
</P>
<P>
It usually takes a while for parties to negotiate into a
coalition in the Netherlands and the longest government-forming
negotiation in the post-war Dutch history was recorded in 1977
when 208 days elapsed before the new cabinet was formed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
