<HEADLINE> EU Dismayed Over Weekend Fighting in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The European Union expressed
Monday its dismay at the reports that intensified hostilities in
Kosovo over the weekend led to more deaths.
</P>
<P>
The union said that the priorities now are a cessation of
hostilities and a start of a meaningful political process.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, Austria, that is now serving the
rotating presidency of the 15-nation union, said that the EU
condemns the alleged recent infiltrations of several hundred
fighters from Albania into the Yugoslav province of Kosovo and
calls urgently on both the armed Kosovar groups and the Serbian
authorities to exercise restraint and to cease hostilities
immediately.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that intensified fightings in Kosovo over
the weekend left up to 450 people unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
The union also demands from the Serbian and Yugoslav
authorities an immediate halt to shellings that had violated the
international borders.
</P>
<P>
The EU stressed that violence will not enhance the prospects
for a negotiated solution of the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
