<HEADLINE> Russia, India in Deal of Designing Nuclear Power Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Russia and India signed a contract
here Monday to prepare a detailed design of a nuclear power plant
in Kudankulam, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed by Viktor Kozlov, general director of
Russia's Atomstroiexport company, and Y.S. Prasad, director of the
Indian Atomic Energy Corp., Itar-Tass quoted the Russian Ministry
of Atomic Power as saying.
</P>
<P>
For actual construction of the nuclear power plant, the two
sides will have to sign another general contract, which is
expected this autumn.
</P>
<P>
The value of the deal has not been revealed yet, but Itar-Tass
quoted Atomic Energy Minister Yevgeny Adamov as saying earlier
that the project would cost 2.6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Russia intends to build two light-water VVER-1000 nuclear
reactors in India on a turn-key basis, Itar-Tass said.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on the construction of a nuclear power plant was
signed in 1988 between India and the former Soviet Union, but
implementation was postponed for lack of funds.
</P>
<P>
Last month, India and Russia, the legal successor to the Soviet
Union, signed an additional agreement that provided the legal
basis for bilateral nuclear cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
