<HEADLINE> Russian Speaker Reassures Turkey Over Cyprus Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of Russia's State Duma
(Lower House) Gennady Seleznyov reassured his Turkish host that
the Russian-made S-300 missiles ordered by Cyprus are only for
defensive purposes.
</P>
<P>
In a joint press conference after meeting with Turkish
counterpart Hikmet Cetin, Seleznyov said that Cyprus is a state
recognized by the United Nations and it can regulate its defense
system as it wishes.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed a deal with Russia early last year to buy the
S-300 missiles with an aim to boost its air defense. But the move
sparked angry reactions from the Turkish Cypriots and Turkey,
which has threatened to launch preemptive strikes to destroy the
missiles if they are deployed.
</P>
<P>
Seleznyov, who arrived here Sunday for a one-day visit, said
that within the framework of the commercial deal between Cyprus
and Russia, the S-300 missiles would be delivered to Cyprus
late this year.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since July 20, 1974 when Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the
Mediterranean island after a failed coup by the Greek Cypriots
seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared in 1983 the
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which is only recognized by
Turkey, to counter the internationally acknowledged Republic of
Cyprus dominated by the Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been stationing over 35,000-strong troops in
northern Cyprus with the claimed aim to protect the Turkish
Cypriot minority.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkey repeated its warning Monday that it would
retaliate against any provocations by the Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
In a congratulatory message to Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash on the 24th anniversary of Turkey's military intervention
in Cyprus, Turkish President Suleyman Demirel said that "Turkey
will retaliate if the Turkish Cypriot community is in danger."
</P>
<P>
Demirel pledged that Turkey would carry out its promise to
defend freedom and rights of the Turkish Cypriots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
