<HEADLINE> Russia Vows Dramatic Increase in Tax Collection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government has pledged
to the International Monetary Fund to fundamentally increase tax
collection next year, the Itar-Tass news agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement addressed to the IMF, the Russian
government and the Central Bank said a complete list of major
tax payers would be drawn up and measures would be taken to ensure
that they pay up.
</P>
<P>
Other steps for more tax revenue include simpler individual
income tax rates, higher land rent and taxes on gambling.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Central Bank promised to make its operations
more transparent and set mandatory requirements on commercial
banks for greater transparency.
</P>
<P>
The moves were seen as efforts taken by the Russian government
to meet conditions set by the IMF and other international
financial institutions for release of vital bail-out loans to help
Russia tide over its economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Russia announced last Monday that it would get 22.6 billion
U.S. dollars from the IMF, the World Bank and Japan in 1998-1999.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Russian President Boris Yeltsin
instructed the government to submit the draft budget for 1999 to
the State Duma, or lower house of parliament, before August 26.
</P>
<P>
In a presidential decree, Yeltsin said the draft should
envision revenues of no less than 376 billion rubles (about 60.5
billion U.S. dollars) and spending of no more than 456 billion
rubles (about 73.5 billion dollars). The ceiling for the budget
deficit is set at 80 billion rubles (about 13 billion dollars), or
2.8 percent of the projected gross domestic product (GDP),
Itar-Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
Also Monday, Russia Vice-Prime Minister Viktor Khristenko told
reporters that the government may sell its stakes in Rosneft,
Slavneft, the United Energy System of Russia, LUKoil, Svyazinvest
and some other major conglomerates to boost productivity,
profitability and competitiveness and generate more jobs.
</P>
<P>
More importantly, the government hopes to increase budget
revenues through such privatization schemes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
