<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Meet on AIDS in Eastern, Southern Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 20 (Xinhua) -- About 63 experts from 12 eastern
and southern African countries gathered here Monday over how to
tackle HIV/AIDS in workplaces in sub-Saharan Africa which sees
the fastest HIV/AIDS spread in the world.
</P>
<P>
HIV carriers now make up 7.4 percent of all those aged 15 to
49 in the region, according to a U.N. report.
</P>
<P>
"Within the sub-continent, HIV rates have been found to be
higher in the military, in educated and skilled groups, in urban
areas and in migrant employment," said Dr Rene Loewenson at the
meeting scheduled to end Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As a result, "workplaces have had more frequent and longer
periods of absenteeism, losses in skills and experience,
diminishing returns to training investments, with an overall
shift to younger and less experienced workers" in the region, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
"On average, an estimated 15 years of working life will be
lost per employee due to AIDS," he quoted data from the
International Labor Organization as saying.
</P>
<P>
Losses due to AIDS have cost formal sector business on average
between 20 and 200 U.S. Dollars per worker per year, with further
unmeasured but significant costs in the informal and household
sectors, and in terms of social development and morale, he said.
</P>
<P>
The expert suggested that the business response to HIV/AIDS
should be divided into different levels and involve in HIV
prevention, health promotion and care, as well as human resource
development and monitoring and evaluation.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Health Minister Jackson Kalweo also called for more
active and serious participation of the business circle into the
anti-AIDS campaign when opening the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"It is becoming increasingly clear that governments alone are
not able to reduce the transmission of HIV/AIDS so as to mitigate
the social impact of AIDS," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"We in this region (eastern and southern Africa) are in deeper
trouble than we ever knew," he warned.
</P>
<P>
The meeting brings together people from key organizations in
eastern and southern Africa with a role in planning and
implementing programs to reduce the impact of HIV/AIDS in the
workplace.
</P>
<P>
Issues to be discussed also include preventive interventions,
their costs and benefits, approaches to workplace awareness and
behavior change and consulting and testing.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting is organized jointly by UNAIDS, Family
Health International and the Organization of African Trade Union
Unity (OATUU). 
</P>
</TEXT>
