<HEADLINE> Kenyan Tea Prices up at Weekly Export Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan tea prices increased at
the weekly export auction in the Indian Ocean port of Mombasa
Monday, according to a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The rise was due to a strong demand from Pakistan and recent
cool weather which appears to slow tea growth, improve quality
and reduce quantities on offer, tea brokers were quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"Because the quality is better, the more discerning markets
like the U.K. also come in," said Norman Wilson, the managing
director of Africa Tea Brokers (ATB).
</P>
<P>
Brighter and medium BP1s appreciated by 0.05 to 0.15 U.S.
Dollars, while lower mediums were dearer by 0.02 to 0.05 Dollars,
brokers said.
</P>
<P>
Brighter PF1s were a strong feature and advanced by 0.20-0.30
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Tea output in Kenya, a key export earner, is poised to hit a
new high this year thanks to improved weather, better husbandry
and strong global prices, the ATB announced earlier last month.
</P>
<P>
The cumulative figure for the year to April stood at 113.26
million kg, an increase of 58.29 million kg or 106.04 percent
over the previous year, said the Mombasa-based company.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is one of the world's leading producers of black teas,
with a record output of 257 million kg in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
