<HEADLINE> Russia Says Parity of Spy Presence With Seoul Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 20 (Xinhua) -- A top Russian intelligence official
said Monday that it is normal for Russia and South Korea to agree
on an equal number of secret service agents in each other's
diplomatic missions.
</P>
<P>
However, Yuri Kobaladze, head of the press bureau of Russia's
Foreign Intelligence Service, declined to confirm or deny reports
that Seoul had agreed to recall five foreign intelligence agents
working under diplomatic cover, two in Moscow and three in
Vladivostok.
</P>
<P>
"We make no comments on our agreements reached with foreign
colleagues, but we think that there is nothing unusual if each
secret service possess an equal number of its representatives in
another country," the Itar-Tass news agency quoted Kobaladze as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, the South Korean Foreign Ministry announced
that it was recalling five diplomats to reduce its number of
intelligence agents in Russia to the level of Russia's in South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
"The withdrawal is in accordance with an agreement between the
intelligence authorities of both countries," said Foreign Ministry
spokesman Lee Ho-jin.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic row began July 4 when Russia ordered the
expulsion of a South Korean diplomat, Cho Sung-woo, on spying
charges. Four days later, Seoul retaliated by ordering the
expulsion of a Russian diplomat, Oleg N. Abramkin.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Russian Deputy Foreign Minister
Grigory Karasin told the Interfax news agency that Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov would meet his South Korean counterpart,
Park Chung-soo, on the sidelines of an international forum
sponsored by the Association of South East Asian Nations in
Manila, the Philippines, slated for July 26-29.
</P>
<P>
He said the meeting was scheduled on South Korean initiative.
</P>
<P>
"Various aspects of the unpleasant incident in our relations
with South Korea will be discussed to some extent," Karasin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
