<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Kenyan Economy Continues to Slow Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The economic growth rate in Kenya
fell to 1.9 percent between March 1997 and March 1998 from 2.3
percent in the previous year, the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK)
said in the July edition of its Monthly Economic Review.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown, evident in virtually all sectors, was mainly
caused by bad weather, rising costs of inputs, depressed
long-term investment, decline in investor confidence and weak
state of infrastructure, said the CBK.
</P>
<P>
The growth in agricultural production in the east African
country is estimated to have declined to 0.7 percent in the year
to March from 1.2 percent in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Coffee fell by 50 percent in the year to March 1998 compared
with the decline of 20 percent in the year to March 1997 while
sisal fell by 22.8 percent from a three percent decrease.
</P>
<P>
Tea yield was down by 11.5 percent in the year to January 1998
from an increase of six percent over the same period in the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Growth in the manufacturing sector is estimated to have
declined to 1.6 percent in the year to March 1998 from 1.9
percent by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The CBK said the decline was due to power rationing in mid
last year, poor infrastructure, strong competition from cheaper
imports, slack domestic demand associated with declining per
capita incomes and the general decrease in industrial investment
last year.
</P>
<P>
The bank predicted that the worsening performance in this
sector is expected to reverse after the second half of 1998,
citing cheaper and increased supplies of agro-based raw materials
and the re-opening up of the U.S. market for Kenyan textiles.
</P>
<P>
Despite the general repression, Kenya's financial sector
improved in 1997 and early 1998 as a result of investment in
Treasury Bills due to high rates of returns and more efficiency
following the introduction of innovative banking techniques.
</P>
<P>
The growth of trade, restaurants and hotels was estimated to
have declined to 3.4 percent in the year to March 1998 from 3.9
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, transport, storage and communication, which
continue to be troubled by weak infrastructure, estimatedly
dropped to 1.6 percent from 1.8 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, the Central Bank forecast that the gross domestic
product will rebound from the 1.9 percent in the year to March
1998 to 2.7 percent by the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
