<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Clash with Yemen on Disputed Island Confirmed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia has confirmed
that Saudi and Yemeni troops exchanged fire on a contested red sea
island two days ago, the Kuwait News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Interior Minister Prince Nayef Bin Abdel-Aziz said in a
news conference late Monday night that Saudi troops "opened fire
in self-defense" in a gunfire clash with a Yemeni force on the
island.
</P>
<P>
He said three Yemeni guards were killed during the clash Sunday
on Duwaima off the Yemeni coast after Yemeni troops fired on Saudi
positions and wounded a Saudi border guard.
</P>
<P>
However, Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh had charged that
Saudi troops carried out "aggressions" along the border during the
past two months.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbors on the Arabian peninsula share a
2,000-kilometer common border and have a decades-old dispute over
three Red Sea islands and parts of the desert region, where huge
oil reserves are expected, between them.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's exchange of fire continued sporadically for five hours
and left another nine guards injured before the two sides agreed
on a cease-fire later the same day.
</P>
<P>
Nayef said the Yemeni and Saudi authorities agreed on Monday to
maintain the cease-fire and instruct border committees to resolve
the dispute.
</P>
<P>
He said the bodies of the Yemeni soldiers and a Yemeni officer
falling captive will be returned. Yemen's foreign minister was
reportedly to fly to Saudi capital Riyadh later Tuesday in a bid
to ease tension.
</P>
<P>
Yemen is one of the poorest countries in the Arab world while
Saudi Arabia is one of the richest. Their border dispute has led
to clashes in the past, but both seemed reluctant to raise the
skirmishes openly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
