<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primakov's China Visit Step Toward Russia-China Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Russia sees a visit to Beijing by
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov as an important step to prepare
for an informal summit between the presidents of Russia and China,
a senior official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Foreign Minister Grigory Karasin told the Interfax news
agency that Primakov's Beijing trip, scheduled for July 22-25,
represents an important stage in the preparation for the summit
between Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Chinese President
Jiang Zemin in Moscow, in early September.
</P>
<P>
He said Primakov, who is scheduled to leave Moscow later
Tuesday, would primarily discuss with Chinese officials political
issues at bilateral and multilateral levels.
</P>
<P>
Such issues as the financial crisis in Southeast Asia and the
long-term security in the region would also be discussed, Karasin
said.
</P>
<P>
"Contacts between Moscow and Beijing in this sphere play an
important role, and the comparison of views on developments at a
regional and global level is extremely important for both
countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
After the nuclear tests in India and Pakistan, Karasin noted,
the strategic security situation in this region had worsened
seriously. "Possible courses of developments should be discussed
and the approaches of Russia and China to the questions compared,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Moscow and Beijing had acute political
differences, Karasin said: "There are no questions on which the
views of the two countries would cardinally differ."
</P>
<P>
Primakov, who is to arrive in Beijing Wednesday morning, is
also scheduled to fly to Manila, to take part in an ASEAN
ministerial conference, Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
