<HEADLINE> Traffic Re-Opened in Somali Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The four main junctions linking
of the Somali capital Mogadishu opened once again Tuesday for the
traffic following the restoration of the green lines on Monday by
militiamen loyal to Hussein Hajji Bod, one of Ali Mahdi's deputy
chairmen.
</P>
<P>
Bod, who briefly spoke to reporters here, said that the
roads have been opened for the sole interest of the people.
</P>
<P>
"We did not dispatch the militiamen to block the traffic
movements in the first place," said Bod who disassociated himself
from the activities undermining the security situation along the
former green lines that divided Mogadishu in the past seven
years.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about his strength and the prospect of peace in
Mogadishu, Bod merely expressed that no one could suppress his
views regarding the on-going decisions to be made for the
formation of Mogadishu's administration and the opening of the
air and seaports.
</P>
<P>
Bod said there are currently peace negotiations continuing
between the war factions to find a lasting solution for all the
existing problems and that he is optimistic for a quick
settlement.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to the previous history of the capital, the security
situation in south Mogadishu has been much better than the part
controlled by faction leader Ali Mahdi Mohamed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
