<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Unveils Economic Package to Counter Impact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government
announced Tuesday a comprehensive package of measures to counter
the impact of sanctions imposed by the international community due
to the detonation of nuclear devices.
</P>
<P>
The package announced here by Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz at a
press conference was aimed at stabilizing the exchange market,
boosting exports and remittances, restricting non-essential
imports and preventing flight of capital to offset the impact of
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Aziz announced the launching of U.S. dollar bonds with
attractive interest rates coupled with new facilities offered to
both the resident and non-resident foreign currency accounts
holders
</P>
<P>
New foreign exchange regime has been introduced to boost
exports, restrict non-essential imports and divert and increase
remittances through the banking system.
</P>
<P>
As part of the incentives for exporters, a fast track procedure
for payment of refund has been developed through which most
exporters would receive their refunds within seven days.
</P>
<P>
To curb luxury imports, the minister announced a regulatory
custom duty of 100 percent, besides increasing registration fees
for vehicles above 1,800 c.c.
</P>
<P>
The government also announced a limit of 10,000 dollars for
carrying abroad as part of the efforts to stop capital flight and
a prior approval of the State Bank of Pakistan will be needed for
any amount exceeding the limit.
</P>
<P>
"Just as we acted on the May 28 (when Pakistan detonated
nuclear devices) to protect our geo-political security, we must
act now to assure our economic security, without which our
geo-political security cannot be sustained," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We are ready to pay the price for our security."
</P>
<P>
Aziz made it clear that the recent deterioration in Pakistan's
economic situation was due to the extension of sanctions to the
international financial institutions which was not applicable to
them earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Droughts Blight Rice in Vietnam's Center and North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Severe droughts are raging through
the northern and central parts of Vietnam, drying out reservoirs
and threatening the summer and fall harvest from tens of thousands
of hectares of rice crops.
</P>
<P>
A total of 23,000 hectares of summer-autumn rice fields in the
three central provinces of Ha Tinh, Quang Binh and Quang Tri which
are hard hit, Vietnam News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In Ha Tinh province alone, 7,000 of the 32,000 hectares of
summer-autumn crops had suffered because of the dry weather.
</P>
<P>
With 32 of the 34 reservoirs running out of water, 7,000 of
14,000 hectares of summer-autumn rice in Quang Binh province had
been blighted.
</P>
<P>
Residents in Dong Ha township of Quang Tri province and Can Loc
and Ky Anh districts of Ha Tinh province are afflicted with a
water shortage.
</P>
<P>
A heat wave has hit northern provinces of the Red River delta,
one of the rice bowls in the country, withering thousands of
hectares of autumn rice crops.
</P>
<P>
Thirty to 40 percent of the autumn rice acreage is dying in My
Van and Chau Giang districts in the northern province of Hung Yen.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's National Center for Hydro-Meteorology has forecast
that hot weather will last for several more days, and droughts
will spread to remote areas in the north. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
