<HEADLINE> Arafat Visits Egypt for Talks on Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat arrived here Tuesday for talks on the
latest developments of the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is expected to brief Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on
the first high-level direct talks in months between the PNA and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming meeting is part of continued coordination and
consultation between the two leaders, who have been seeking ways
to break the deadlock in the peace process caused by Israel's
building a Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem in March last year
and its overdue troop pullback from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Chief Palestinian negotiator Mahmoud Abbas and Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai on Sunday held a three-hour meeting on
contentious issues blocking the pullout.
</P>
<P>
But Palestinian officials said on Monday that no progress was
made at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The United States has reportedly called on Israel to withdraw
from another 13.1 percent of the West Bank in second redeployment
as required by the Oslo accords. The Palestinians have accepted
the proposal, but Israel resisted it.
</P>
<P>
Israeli right-wing extremists insisted that the proposed scope
of withdrawal will endanger its security interests and no more
than 9 percent should be handed over to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has full or civil control over 27 percent of the West
Bank and the Gaza Strip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
