<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Arafat Discuss Palestinian-Israeli Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat Tuesday briefed Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak on the first direct Palestinian-Israeli talks in months
over Israeli redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived here earlier Tuesday as his deputy Mahmoud Abbas
and Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai completed two days
of talks, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
But the agency gave no details of the Arafat-Mubarak talks.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has proposed a 13 percent more Israeli troop
withdrawal from the West Bank. The Palestinians have accepted the
formula, but Israel rejected it, citing security reasons.
</P>
<P>
At the request of Washington, the two sides resumed the first
direct talks Sunday after 16 months of stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Little progress was reportedly made in the first two rounds of
talks Sunday and Monday. A third round is scheduled to be held
later Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, a key Palestinian ally, has kept a close watch on the
development in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cairo has been pushing for an international
conference to revive the Mideast peace process. The proposal was
made in an Egyptian-French initiative put forward in May.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, who will visit Paris next
week to discuss details of the initiative with his French
counterpart, has said the initiative dovetails the U.S. proposal
on Israeli withdrawal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
