<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Workers Determined to Stage Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Two Korean workers' organizations
announced on Tuesday decisions for 650,000 workers to go on strike
on Wednesday, despite a government warning of tough action.
</P>
<P>
The Korean Metal Workers' Federation said its members will
strike to protest mass layoffs.
</P>
<P>
"A general strike is inevitable unless the government accepts
our demands," a federation spokesman told a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said 50,000 workers of the federation will begin
a general strike after a mass rally in front of the Seoul Station
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The federation, which includes the labor union of Hyundai Motor
Co. and other major manufacturers, urged the government to put an
end to layoffs and prevent illegal labor practices by employers.
</P>
<P>
It will be the second strike by the federation within a week.
Members of the federation across the nation downed tools last
Tuesday and Wednesday, calling for an end to mass layoffs.
</P>
<P>
The Korean Confederation of Trade Unions (KCTU), reaffirmed its
plan to stage an indefinite general strike from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Our 600,000 member workers have no choice but to strike and
fight if the government rejects our call for an end to forced
restructuring of the economy," said the confederation.
</P>
<P>
The government, which has called the strikes as illegal, said
it will take stern action against union leaders and strikers.
</P>
<P>
A manhunt is still underway for 83 union leaders who, police
say, masterminded last week's strikes.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean parliament legalized the mass layoffs last
April after a tripartite commission of the government, management
and labor unions reached an agreement on the layoffs.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed last December with the International
Monetary Fund for a rescue loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars, South
Korea has to restructure its economy, open its markets and shut
down ailing financial institutions and companies this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
