<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Official Praises China's Role in Stablizing Asian Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Joseph E. Stiglitz, chief
economist and senior vice-president of the World Bank, today
praised China's role in stablizing both the Asian and the world
economy.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Stiglitz said that the role
of China in Asia and the world is very important, and China's
effort in keeping the exchange rate of the yuan RMB stable has
helped stablize the economy of the Asian region.
</P>
<P>
"I think the actions taken by the Chinese government are going
to be very supportive to the overall stability of the region," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis which began last July has lasted
longer and has been deeper than most people expected, he
noted. The depth of the downturn in the region's economy is very
severe, and most people are now forecasting a relatively slow
recovery in the region.
</P>
<P>
He also said that China has recognized the consequences of the
Southeast Asian financial crisis and has committed itself to
compensating for weak exports by increasing domestic demand, which
is very important.
</P>
<P>
However, he acknowledged that it often takes a while for
economic policies to have actual effects, as monetary policy
usually has a lag of between six to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that at this junction the most important
thing is to maintain a strong economy, and that is what is
happening in China. Chinese financial authorities understand the
nature of the financial problems and are very committed to
addressing them.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he expressed his full confidence about the long-run
prospects for the Asian economy, saying that the fundamentals of
the Asian economy remain strong, which in the long run will ensure
a high level of growth.
</P>
<P>
Western economies have had periodic recessions every four to
six years, while many Asian countries have enjoyed economic growth
for two to three decades, therefore one should not be too upset by
an episode of recession, he said.
</P>
<P>
Stiglitz, who began his China visit on July 19, will leave on
July 25.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
