<HEADLINE> Bomb Kills 1 SLA, Wounds 2 in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A member of the Israeli-allied
South Lebanon Army (SLA) was killed and two others wounded in
Tuesday by a roadside bomb, the National Broadcast Network radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
The bomb was detonated by anti-Israeli guerrillas when a SLA
armored personnel carrier was patrolling near the town of Jezzine,
in Israeli occupied south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In Beirut, the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God,
claimed responsibility for the attack, saying at least four SLA
members were killed or wounded.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation, Israeli warplanes raided villages in the Iqlim
al Toufah area, a Hezbollah stronghold on the edge of the occupied
zone. There is no immediate report of casualties.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer self-styled security
zone in south Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting
its north from Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then the 1,500 Israeli occupying troops and the
2,500-member SLA have been locked in a war of attrition there with
Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by Hezbollah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
