<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Blames Iraq Over POW Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Head of the Iranian Commission
for Prisoners of War (POWs) Abdollah Najafi on Tuesday blamed
Iraq for lacking sincerity in solving the POW issue.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has not given accounts of the fate of 3,738 Iranian POWs
who Iran holds firm evidence to show that they were captured
by the Iraqi forces during the 1980-88 war, the official news
agency IRNA quoted Najafi as saying.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has said that a number of Iranian POWs have died and some
others are unwilling to return home. But Najafi said that Iran
would not accept the Iraqi claim unless the International
Committee of Red Cross confirms it.
</P>
<P>
He expressed dismay over the slow pace of implementing the
accord between the two countries on the POW issue, criticizing
Iraq for failing to fully honor its commitments.
</P>
<P>
"If the trend continues, we will not reach a desirable
result," he said.
</P>
<P>
Najafi's remarks seemed to contradict his earlier statement
Friday that the names listed as POWs of the two countries had
become clear in the recent talks between Iranian and Iraqi
officials. He expected the POW issue to be fully clarified within
the next few months.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister for Arab-African affairs Seyed
Mohammad Sadr also said Saturday that Tehran and Baghdad would
finally settle the POW issue within six months and all Iranian
POWs would return home under a timetable to be set by the sides.
</P>
<P>
During the past eight years, Iran has exchanged 54,776 Iraqi
POWs for 39,364 Iranian detainees. But it is still unclear how
many Iranian and Iraqi POWs are still held by the other side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
