<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- Gold imports of Dubai fell to 244 tonnes in the first
half of this year, down 20 percent from 307.8 tons in the same
period last year, the Arabic daily Al Hayat reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The drop in Dubai's gold imports was attributed to the decline
of consumption by Indian markets, one of the world's biggest
consuming markets of this precious metal.
</P>
<P>
Dubai is considered the world's biggest trading center of gold
ingots.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The profits of the Gulf Airways during the first
half of this year will reach 25 million U.S. dollars from 10
million in the same period last year, the United Arab Emirates
Newspaper Al Itihad reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The company's Executive President for Financial and Strategy
Affairs of Walter Van West was quoted as saying that the company
anticipated the doubling of operation profits this year.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that the company would purchase six Airbus planes
equipped with the latest technology at a cost of 600 million
dollars. The new planes will join the operating fleet in mid-1999,
in anticipation of the company's new plans for the coming century.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Airways earned 48 million dollars in profits in the
past year.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Three Egyptian-Chinese joint ventures, with an
investment of 5 million U.S. dollars, will be established in the
Port Said free zone to produce recorder cassettes, measurement sets
and plastic products, the Arabic Al Akhbar reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Egyptian Petroleum Authority has
decided to offer nine new areas in northern Sinai and the Suez
Gulf to world companies for oil prospection. October 29 has been
set as the deadline for tenders.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The price of Egyptian car spare parts will decline in
the next two months due to rising imports and abundant supply.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Egyptian Federation of Chambers of Commerce
attributed the price drop partially to the fact that spare parts
ordered from Japan, Taiwan and Malaysia will arrive in Egypt in
succession as of mid-August.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume of car spare parts in Egypt is estimated at
over 200 million Egyptian pounds (58.8 million dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The handling capacity of Saudi local trading and
industrial harbors, excluding that of crude oil, has surpassed 44
million tonnes in the first half of this year, up 10 percent over
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
A recent statement released by the General Authority for Saudi
Arabian harbors in Riyadh showed that exports constituted 70
percent of the total handling capacity, and imports 30 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
