<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Supports Arab Summit With Clear Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel Meguid Tuesday expressed support to Egypt's stance that an
Arab summit should be convened with well-defined objectives to
rescue the faltering peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The league backs President Hosni Mubarak's assertion that an
Arab summit should be capable of adopting effective and
influential decisions," he spoke from Vienna in a telephone
interview with the Cairo-based Voice of Arabs Radio.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak Monday renewed his support for holding an expanded Arab
summit on the ailing Mideast peace process, which has been
demanded by the Palestinians for months. But he stressed that good
preparation was needed to clearly define the summit's goals in
order to come up with strong resolutions.
</P>
<P>
A string of coordination talks on the timing, venue and agenda
of the summit were held in Arab capitals in June, but so far there
is no indication that the summit is upcoming.
</P>
<P>
Meguid noted that there had been an international response to
the Arab wish to salvage the peace march.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that his ongoing European tour, which started
Monday and will also take him to Austria and Poland, highlighted
the Arab wish to promote the Euro-Arab relations in various fields.
</P>
<P>
He said he would discuss with Austrian and Polish officials the
feasibility of giving a push to the peace process based on the
Egyptian-French initiative.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been stalled for 16
months over Israel's construction of a new settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem and its long-delayed withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Upset by the prolonged deadlock due to Israel's intransigence,
Egypt and France called in May for convening an international
conference to save the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Cautious optimism has surfaced in the past days after Israel
and the Palestinian side resumed their direct talks Sunday night
in an effort to clinch a deal on the overdue redeployment and
other issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
