<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Says Israeli Demands Unrealistic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
said Tuesday that nothing new has come out of the recent
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks as Israel was expecting an
impossible compromise from the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"Apparently nothing new has so far been offered by the Israelis
to the Palestinians during their recent talks," the top Egyptian
diplomat told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
In statements following the talks between Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak and Palestinian National Authority President Yasser
Arafat held earlier in the day, Moussa said that Arafat briefed
Mubarak on the outcome of Israeli-Palestinian talks held this week
in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Among the key issues discussed was the U.S. initiative calling
for an additional 13 percent Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank
in the second stage of further redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Arafat was not optimistic since the Israelis offered nothing
new to the Palestinians during the talks, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
"Palestinians so far have accepted the U.S. initiative while
the Israelis rejected it. The Israelis expect concessions the
Palestinians will not give," he added.
</P>
<P>
On his visit to France next Monday, Moussa said he and the
French officials would study means to activate the Egyptian-French
initiative that calls for an international conference to salvage
the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
"In case the peace process should come to a full stop and face
absolute failure, the international community should know the
whole issue and the reasons behind this failure," he said.
</P>
<P>
As the 16-month deadlock in the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks
drags on, Egypt is expecting the Franco-Egyptian initiative to
work in a way that "dovetails" the U.S. plan.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said the U.S. has no objection to the Egyptian-French
initiative which only needs "more polishing" that could be
completed during his forthcoming visit to France.
</P>
<P>
He also dismissed as "incorrect" the speculation about a
possible U.S. withdrawal from the whole process, saying that
Washington would continue to play its role to achieve the success
of the peace march. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
