<HEADLINE> Kiriyenko Sees IMF Loan As Government Victory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko on Tuesday said the stabilization loan of 11.2 billion
U.S. dollars from the International Monetary Fund (IMF) was an
indisputable victory for his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko told a press conference that the loan approval by the
IMF came after the Russian government had made up for the
rejection by the State Duma, the lower house of Russian
parliament, of several stabilization bills.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet's program paved the way for the approval of the
loan, he said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF Board of Directors decided Monday to appropriate a new
package of 11.2 billion dollars of aid to Russia, but the first
tranche Moscow can receive immediately was slashed to 4.8 billion
dollars, instead of the expected 5.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
News of the cut hit the Russian stock market, with Tuesday's
prices of blue chips slipping three to five percent in the Russian
Trading System.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the shortfall of 80 million dollars, Kiriyenko
said successful implementation of the program to exchange
government treasury bills for Eurobonds would allow the government
to offset the decrease.
</P>
<P>
He expressed satisfaction that the overall size of the
stabilization loan, 11.2 billion dollars, was not reduced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
