<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Akayev Can Run For Third Term, Says Constitutional Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Kyrgyz President Askar Akayevich
Akayev will be eligible to run for re-election in 2000, the
Kazakhstan Pravda daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kyrgyzstan's Constitutional Court returned a verdict recently,
legalizing Akayev's campaign for another term of presidency, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the year, some parliamentarians of Kyrgyzstan issued
a statement opposing Akayev's campaign for re-election.
</P>
<P>
They held that the Constitution barred one from being president
for more than two consecutive terms, so Akayev, who was elected as
president in 1990 and again in 1995, could not run for another
term.
</P>
<P>
But other parliamentarians and supporters of Akayev argued that
1995-2000 should be Akayev's first presidential term because the
1990 presidential election was held under the old Constitution,
which was approved in the former Soviet era and expired in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The verdict by the Constitutional Court has been widely
welcomed in Kyrgyzstan because many people hope that the reform
process can continue in Kyrgyzstan if Akayev is re-elected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
