<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourist Arrivals in Singapore Continue to Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals in Singapore in
the first half of the year declined by 17 percent to three million
compared with a year ago, according to figures released Tuesday by
the Singapore Tourism Association (STB).
</P>
<P>
The figures also showed that tourist arrivals in June dropped
by 19.8 percent from the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
According to STB's outlining review on the performance in June
in comparison with a year ago, visitors from Indonesia,
Singapore's largest visitor-generating market, declined by some 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
Visitors from Japan, another Singapore's largest tourism
market, registered a loss of some 26 percent because of the
sluggish economic conditions in that country.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, the third largest source of visitors, saw a sharp
drop of about 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, visitors from Hong Kong grew by over nine percent due
to competitive packages offered by some airline companies during
the month, the STB said.
</P>
<P>
The STB said the continued decline in tourist arrivals from
ASEAN countries was prompted by their domestic economic
difficulties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shishigina makes winning return at Asian champion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Asian record holder Olga Shishigina
of Kazakhstan celebrated her return to the track by taking the
women's 100-meter hurdles title at the Asian Athletic
Championships in Fukuoka, Japan, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year-old, ending her two-year suspension for using
banned drugs in February this year, set a new championship record
of 13.04 seconds for her first victory after the comeback.
</P>
<P>
China's Feng Yun finished second in 13.10 with a slippery start
after the rain, followed by defending champion Sriyani Kulawansa
of Sri Lanka in 13.16.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the afternoon, heavy rain and thunder halted the
competition for some two hours, forcing the organizers to postpone
the women's discus, pole vault, triple jump, men's discus and high
jump until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the morning's events, Chinese runners took a one-two finish
in the women's 800 meters and men's 110 meters hurdles with Zhang
Jian and Chen Yanhao taking China's 11th and 12th gold medals.
</P>
<P>
Zhang clocked 2:01.16 to beat Liu Jing by 0.69 seconds and
Jyotirmoy Sikdhar of India by 1.49 seconds, with all three
clocking new championship records.
</P>
<P>
Chen won the 110 meters hurdles in 13.53, ahead of Qi Zhen in
13.74 and Andrey Sklyarenko of Kazakhstan in 13.86.  
</P>
</TEXT>
