<HEADLINE> Lebanese National Carrier to Form Alliance with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's national carrier, the
Middle East Airlines (MEA), is expected to form an alliance with
its French counterpart Air France next month, the Daily Star
newspaper reported here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The alliance will be signed in Beirut next month and the deal
will come into effect in April next year," Mohammed Hout, MEA's
chairman said in an interview with the paper.
</P>
<P>
He said if the overall cooperation succeeds, MEA passengers
would be able to book from Beirut into the Air France network of
more than 100 destinations.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the alliance will increase accessibilities to
and from the United States and South America.
</P>
<P>
Another significant feature of the deal will see MEA
passengers who will be able to participate in a frequent flyer
program by joining the one run by Air France and several of its
partner airlines around the world.
</P>
<P>
In return, Hout said, Air France passengers will benefit from
MEA's strength in the region as the MEA's routes to Kuwait and the
Far East would be attractive to Air France passengers.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the biggest airlines in the world have formed
partnerships with each other," the chairman said, "If we want
Beirut to become a regional hub, we have to make it possible for
passengers to connect around the world."
</P>
<P>
Until two years ago Air France had a 25 percent stake in MEA,
which is now owned by Lebanon's central bank.
</P>
<P>
Hout has been given three years to turn the airlines around
from its disastrous recent past which includes a loss of 100
million U.S. dollars in the last fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
