<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Society Conference Opens in Geneva </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The eighth annual meeting of the
Internet Society (ISOC) conference, known as the Internet summit
in the industry, began here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
One of the major issues at the conference will be the future of
the Internet's domain naming system, said the U.S.-based ISOC, the
organizer of the event on July 21-24.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from more than 120 countries and regions are
expected to discuss the next major steps to assist the Internet
Assigned Names Authority (IANA) in defining and developing a
non-profit corporation.
</P>
<P>
ISOC expects that about 4,000 stake-holders, policy makers and
Internet leaders around the world will be attending the conference.
</P>
<P>
The Network Training Workshops of ISOC, held annually since
1993, have helped some developing countries in Asia, the former
Soviet Union and more than 20 African countries to set up Internet
connections and to have individuals trained in the technical and
operational aspects of establishing and managing network system.
</P>
<P>
Another training system of ISOC, named "Hands-on", will be
given to professionals who will play a vital role in establishing
the Internet's presence in their countries or facilitating the
efforts of schools, government organizations, firms, and residents
to learn about and exploit Internet services.
</P>
<P>
As the conference is not a purely technical one, 11 tutorials
will be set up to help visitors understand the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The Internet Society is a U.S.-based non-profit international
organization. Since 1992, it has served as the international
organization for global coordination and cooperation on the
Internet, promoting and maintaining a broad spectrum of activities
focused on the Internet's development, availability and associated
technologies.
</P>
<P>
The first Internet Society Conference was held in 1991, when an
estimated four million people had access to the Internet. By 1997,
the number has risen to 57 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
