<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, U.S to Cooperate on Energy-Saving Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Ministry of Science
and Technology and the U.S. Department of Energy have agreed to
cooperate on a commercial building which will showcase
energy-saving technologies, sources said.
</P>
<P>
China's Science and Technology Vice-Minister Deng Nan and
U.S. Ambassador to China James Sasser signed the Statement of Work
recently to explore designs for a medium-sized commercial office
building in downtown Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The building, if constructed, would develop energy efficient
design criteria and serve as a center for research on energy
efficiency and renewable energy technologies.
</P>
<P>
According to Lu Xuedu, an official of the Science and
Technology Ministry, this is the first time China and the United
States have begun practical cooperation under the obligation of
the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change.
</P>
<P>
The framework convention stipulates that developed countries
are required to reduce their "greenhouse" gas emissions. It also
provides for developing countries to obtain help with technologies
and funding to increase energy efficiency and reduce emissions.
</P>
<P>
China has already started to cooperate with Japan and Norway in
this field. Cooperation includes the three-billion-yen coke
project between the Capital Steel Group and Japan, an iron alloy
project and a dust-burning project, both with Japan, and the
themopower project between Shangqiu city in Henan Province and
Norway.
</P>
<P>
Lu said the energy-efficient building demonstration project,
with the United States providing designs and technologies, sets an
example for bilateral cooperation under the Framework Convention,
and helps build communication and trust between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
The commercial building, including a laboratory for
demonstrating energy efficiency, would also serve as the office
for China's Agenda 21 agency, a national effort to pursue
sustainable development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
