<HEADLINE> Navigation on Yangtze River to Resume Tomorrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The temporary shiplock of Three
Gorges Dam Project is scheduled to resume operation at eight
o'clock tomorrow after being shut down because of recent heavy
floods.
</P>
<P>
"If the water level on the river does not rise tonight, the
shiplock is expected to reopen tomorrow morning," said Zhang
Qingsong, director of the Yangtze Navigation Administration Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said the shiplock is ready to resume operation since the
water flow through the Three Gorges Dam Project has now dropped to
44,500 cubic meters per second. The shiplock was closed after the
water flow rose to 45,000 cubic meters per second several days ago.
</P>
<P>
More than 980 passenger ships were stranded at Yichang, and all
150,000 passengers on board were moved to safety.
</P>
<P>
However, Zhang said, the river canal at the Three Gorges Dam
will not be opened until the water flow drops below 40,000 cubic
meters per second.
</P>
<P>
According to weather forecasts, heavy rains might fall at the
upper reaches of Yangtze River in the next few days, and the
Three Gorges Dam may have to suspend navigation for a third time
if the water level hits 45,000 cubic meters again, Zhang added.
</P>
<P>
The third peak flood passed through the site of the Three
Gorges Dam Project in the early morning of July 18, and the water
flow remained above 53,000 cubic meters per second for two
consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
The water level began to drop slowly on July 21, and stood at
44,500 cubic meters per second at 6:00 p.m. today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
