<HEADLINE> Crooked Parliamentary Candidates to Be Punished </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 21 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
said that parliamentary candidates who engaged in vote-buying and
smear campaigns in Tuesday's one re-election and six by-elections
will be punished by law.
</P>
<P>
"It has yet to be ascertained, but it seems that there have
been such cases," Kim said on Tuesday in response to media reports
that some candidates had tried to buy votes.
</P>
<P>
"Those engaged in any illegal and illegitimate election
activities will face stern legal action by prosecutors and the
police," the president told reporters after he cast his ballot for
the by-election in Chongno district.
</P>
<P>
Chongno is one of the seven districts which began polling to
fill National Assembly (parliament) seats vacated by members
convicted of crimes, and those who had died or resigned to run in
local elections.
</P>
<P>
Television stations here have predicted that the ruling
coalition, composed of the National Congress for New Politics and
United Liberal Democrats, will win four out of the seven districts.
</P>
<P>
By 5:00 p.m., a low voter turnout of 36.2 percent was
registered, which was blamed on public indifference caused by the
current financial crisis, TV reports said.
</P>
<P>
The final result of the elections, which will come out late
Tuesday night, will determine whether or not the opposition Grand
National Party, now with 147 seats in the 299-member parliament,
can retain its majority status. 
</P>
