<HEADLINE> ASEAN Not to Change Free Trade Area Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The nine members of the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) are not keen on scaling down
the completion of their ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) commitments,
ASEAN Director General Rodolfo Severino said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Members have reaffirmed again and again that the commitment to
AFTA's schedule remains," Severino told reporters. "The only
debate is how much to accelerate the completion of AFTA and in
what way."
</P>
<P>
Severino said that ASEAN leaders and ministers are in fact
exploring the possibility of moving more products from the
temporary exclusion list to the inclusion list whose tariffs will
be lowered.
</P>
<P>
"They have also addressed the questions of making trade easier
through measures such as harmonization of customs laws and
procedures and tariff rates, and computerization," he said.
</P>
<P>
Amid high inflation rates and negative growths caused by the
lingering currency crisis, he said, ASEAN leaders have agreed to
aggressively implement measures deemed to be crucial at ending the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
These include the call for ASEAN major markets to open their
markets wider to ASEAN products; strengthening of regional
economic integration; the establishment of surveillance mechanism
which reflects movement of capital and macroeconomic indicators;
and the use of ASEAN currencies for intra-ASEAN trade.
</P>
<P>
"We should not expect, however, that these measures would
result in overnight recovery," Severino said. "But economic
recovery would be possible in two to three years."
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN Standing Committee (ASC) and the ASEAN Senior
Officials Meeting (SOM) opened here separately Tuesday to prepare
for the ASEAN Ministerial Meeting and its related meetings. Both
ASC and SOM will end Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Vietnam, Singapore, Thailand, the Philippines,
Indonesia, Malaysia, Laos, Brunei and Myanmar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
