<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Water Crisis Blamed On Waste and Pollution (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists say that
wasted resources and pollution are the major causes of China's
water shortage and that it may become a major crisis by the
mid-21st century.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese still believe that water supply in their country
is inexhaustible and do not try to find ways to improve water use,
according to Chen Mengxiong, of the Chinese Academy of Sciences
(CAS).
</P>
<P>
China has more than 2,800 billion cu.m. of water, but with only
a per-capita share of 2,700 cu.m., a fourth of the world's
average, and even though theirs is a water deficient country,
people still squander water resources and water pollution is
getting worse, Chen told an international symposium on water in
Changchun, the capital of northeast China's Jilin Province, last
week.
</P>
<P>
About 70 percent of the water used for irrigation, or half of
the country's total water consumption, has been wasted because of
a low utilization rate, he said, and a fifth of China's rivers are
polluted to varying extent, and 5 percent of them have serious
pollution.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that some 70 percent of China's fresh water
may not be available for direct use by the beginning of the next
century because of grave pollution from waste water discharge, and
that at least 300 cities are suffering from water shortages, and
approximately 20 million ha. of arable land is hit by dry spells
each year.
</P>
<P>
Ground subsidence and seawater are becoming problems becuse of
the over-use of groundwater in some coastal cities like Shanghai
and Tianjin, Chen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Gives Priority to Rural Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Promoting rural development and
improving the lives of the poor in the rural areas is one of the
major goals of the Philippine government led by President Joseph
Estrada, Agriculture Secretary William Dar said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dar said that strategic agricultural and fishery programs
should be implemented to materialize this goal, which Estrada has
promised to the people.
</P>
<P>
Dar said these programs should ensure food security and provide
livelihood opportunities particularly to the small, marginal
farmers and fisher folk.
</P>
<P>
Such programs include the putting up of new irrigation systems
in additional 600,000 hectares of agricultural land.
</P>
<P>
Dar said that at present, out of the 1.4 million hectares of
irrigated farmland in the country, only 20 percent or around
270,000 hectares are in Mindanao, the Philippines' second-largest
island.
</P>
<P>
More irrigation projects should be built in Mindanao which has
an irrigable area of 960,000 hectares, he said.
</P>
<P>
"While we are pursuing big irrigation projects, preferably
under build-operate-transfer schemes, we will also focus on
cost-efficient, high impact small irrigation systems, tapping vast
shallow underground sources," he said.
</P>
<P>
Field surveys show that an additional 1.6 million hectares of
farmland can be irrigated across the country through small systems
such as impoundments, reservoirs and shallow tube wells.
</P>
<P>
Poor agriculture infrastructures including irrigation systems
have hindered the development of the country's agriculture
industry and its rural areas, home to two-thirds of its 70 million
population.
</P>
<P>
Because of its backward agriculture, the Philippines has to
import millions of tons of rice to ease food shortage in the
country. Nearly 1.3 million tons of rice have been imported by the
country this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
