<HEADLINE> Indonesia's House Commission Approves Bill on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's House of
Representatives' (DPR) Commission on Foreign Affairs approved a
bill on the anti-torture convention here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The bill was approved by all factions of the commission during
its third working meeting.
</P>
<P>
Now, the House commission will present the bill at the House
during its plenary meeting on July 24 for passing into a law.
</P>
<P>
After chairing the meeting, the House commission's chief Aisyah
Amini told reporters that it was the first time in more than 30
years for the DPR to use its right to propose a bill.
</P>
<P>
"The bill was proposed at the initiative of the DPR. This is a
record for the legislative body," she said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas told the meeting that
the passing of the bill on the anti-torture convention into a law
would be a historical event for the country not only because of
its content, but also because it was done at the initiative of the
DPR.
</P>
<P>
The convention is part of a series of international conventions
on human rights.
</P>
<P>
"We still have the task of preparing a convention on
anti-racial discrimination which is also part of the international
convention on human rights," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The official approval of the convention at the (DPR) plenary
meeting will be an initial step. But the most important thing is
that the government, the people and all agencies will implement
the convention," Alatas added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
