<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 300 People Killed in Car Accidents in Addis Ababa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Traffic accidents in Addis
Ababa, the capital of Ethiopia, increased sharply during the
just-ended 1997/98 fiscal year with a total of 300 deaths in
about 9,710 car accidents.
</P>
<P>
Befekadu Tolera, Head of the Addis Ababa Traffic Control and
Inspection Office, said the 300 deaths represented a 17 percent
increase over the death toll of the previous year, the Ethiopian
Herald newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the 300 deaths, 2,340 people
sustained light or serious injuries while property valued at 1.66
million U.S.Dollars were destroyed, Befekadu said.
</P>
<P>
Addis Ababa has the highest rate of traffic accidents in the
world, Befekadu said. He belived that that drivers and roads are the
major causes for the accidents.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Addis Ababa administration is paying special
attention to harmonizing the annual growth rate of
7.6 percent in the number of cars with the 3.8 percent population
growth rate in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
He said that efforts are being taken to overcome this problems
by issuing driving licenses only to competent drivers and by
checking condition of vehicles.
</P>
<P>
There is a plan to effect attitudinal changes in the society
especially in relation to the implementation of the newly
introduced traffic regulation, said Befekadu.
</P>
<P>
The Addis Ababa administration introduced on july 8, 1998 a
new road safety regulation to contain traffic irregularities in
the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
