<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1.7 Million Cataract Sufferers Hope to Regain Sight by 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, July 21 (Xinhua) -- More than 340,000 cataract
sufferers have regained sight since the SightFirst China Action
was launched last year and health officials have pledged to cure
1.7 million people by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
According to Sun Jinzhong, an official with the Chinese
Disabled Persons Federation (CDPF) who is in charge of the project,
China has received 15 million U.S. dollars in aid from the Lions
Clubs which is co-sponsoring the action along with the CDPF and the
Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
China has some four million cataract patients and the number is
growing by 400,000 a year. Most patients are in financial straits
because of their poor vision, and they live mostly in
poverty-stricken rural areas.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony held today for the SightFirst China
Action hospital in Liaoning Province in north China, Sun said
China plans to send 250 medical teams to poor and remote areas and
provide operations for cataract sufferers over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The medical teams will also run training courses in those areas
to ensure that the sufferers get proper and professional care from
local medical networks.
</P>
<P>
The SightFirst China Action helps cataract patients recover
their sight by replacing the diseased crystalline lens. This
method has had a high success rate and is relatively inexpensive.
</P>
<P>
Sun said China used to carry out some 50,000 cataract
operations a year. But last year 348,000 such procedures were
performed, costing just over 2,000 yuan each (about 250
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said more hospitals will be designated as SightFirst China
Action facilities, and the cost of surgery is expected to drop to
around 1,200 yuan for each case (about 150 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
