<HEADLINE> Ho Chi Minh City Hard Hit by Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam's largest
economic hub, has been hit hard by the Asian financial crisis this
year, the Vietnam Investment Review said in the latest issue.
</P>
<P>
The report said exports from the city dropped to 1.9 billion
U.S. dollars over the past six months, a 0.6 percent fall compared
to the same period last year, and are expected to continue falling
during the remaining months of the year.
</P>
<P>
Exports by Vietnamese companies dropped 6.5 percent to 1.5
billion U.S. dollars, while foreign-invested exports increased
45.4 percent, said the English-language weekly.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Hong Kong fell by 51 percent, while exports to China
fell by 40 percent. The Indonesia and Philippine markets showed
increased interest in Vietnamese exports.
</P>
<P>
The signs are worrying for Vietnamese government, as the
exports of the southern capital, Ho Chi Minh City, handled 50
percent of the nation's total exports and 30 percent of the
domestic goods turnover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
