<HEADLINE> S'pore, U.S. Navies Start 4th Bilateral Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Navies of Singapore and the
United States started their fourth bilateral exercises as of
Monday which will last until July 31, according to a press release
from the Ministry of Defense Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The press release said that the opening ceremony for the
exercises, which are being conducted under the Cooperation Afloat
Readiness and Training (CARAT), was co-officiated at Tuas Naval
Base Monday morning by Commodore Frank Guest, Commander of
Squadron 31, USN, and Colonel Ronnie Tay, Commander of First
Flotilla, RSN.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Naval Task Force from the U.S. Seventh Fleet has been
deployed to the region for bilateral exercises with countries in
Southeast Asia, it said.
</P>
<P>
According to the press release, a total of about 800 officers
and men from both navies are participating in the maneuvers which
are involving 12 ships, one submarine, maritime patrol aircraft,
strike warplanes and divers. Their activities include encounter,
anti-submarine, salvage exercises, explosive and ordnance disposal
exercises, maritime patrol aircraft interaction activities,
medical and logistics exchange activities and
humanitarian/disaster relief discussions, it said.
</P>
<P>
Aircraft to be sent by Singapore Air Force and the U.S. Air
Forces are also involved in the exercises, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
