<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Welcomes Nigeria's New Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Commonwealth Secretary-General
Emeka Anayoku has expressed welcome to the further release of
political prisoners and the new transition program announced by
Nigerian Head of State General Abdulsalam Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
The release of political prisoners and detainees by the
Nigerian authorities and the new program of transition to
democracy announced by General Abubakar Monday provide "further
evidence of his commitment to national reconciliation and the
establishment of a credible process to democracy in Nigeria,"
Anyaoku said, quoted by the Post Express Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In his nationally televised address Monday night, Abubakar
announced to free all political prisoners and set May 29, 1999 as
the new date for the military to handover power to an elected
civilian president, in stead of the originally planned October 1,
this year.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to Abubakar's address, Anyaoku said he particularly
welcomed the announcement of the "new independent electoral
commission which, with appropriate powers, should contribute to
the credibility of the electoral process in Nigeria."
</P>
<P>
"It is my sincere hope that the new transition program
announced by the head of state will lead to an open and
transparent political process in which all Nigerians can
participate," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth secretary general, who comes from Nigeria,
visited his home country early this month to discuss with
Abubakar issues concerning Nigeria's political transition and
relations with the Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
According to Anyaoku, the 53-nation organization, which has been
pressing for a return to democracy in Nigeria, will wish to
follow closely the implementation of the new transition program.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar, in his national broadcast, scrapped all the political
parties and transition institutions, including the National
Electoral Commission of Nigeria, and canceled all the elections
conducted on the basis of them.
</P>
<P>
The head of state announced that fresh elections will begin
later this year, with presidential election held in the first
quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
The international community, particularly the United Nations,
the Commonwealth, the Organization of African Unity and other
relevant organizations, will observe the elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
