<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Seeks International Understanding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar has appealed the international community for
understanding in his government's efforts toward resolving the
socio-economic and political problems in the country.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar in a national broadcast Monday night said the present
administration would consolidate existing relationship and
maintain positive and friendly relations with all nations of the
world.
</P>
<P>
This will be done "without compromise to our sovereignty and
independence as we endeavor to defend and protect the legitimate
interest of our sub-region on all issues", said the soft-spoken
general, who came to power after the sudden death of his
predecessor Sani Abacha six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Noting that "every country is saddled with problems and
possibilities that are unique to it," Abubakar urged the
country's foreign friends extend "a level of understanding and
respect desired of all sovereign nations".
</P>
<P>
"We implore our friends to exercise patience and appreciate
the unique problems that face us as a nation", said the
56-year-old head of state.
</P>
<P>
This is against the background that as the world become
increasingly inter-dependent, "our actions at home as a people
are always interpreted in the context of the cherished norms of
international morality and behavior," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has in the last five years come under intense
criticism both within and outside mainly for its poor human right
record and lack of democracy.
</P>
<P>
Western powers, particularly the United States and the
European Union (EU), and the Commonwealth have imposed sanctions
against Nigeria, thereby creating for it the image of a pariah
state.
</P>
<P>
However, the west seems to be soft-pedaling its diplomatic
isolation against Nigeria since the visits earlier this months by
Tony Lloyd, British Minister of State and EU representative,
United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Commonwealth
Secretary-General Emeka Anyaoku and U.S. Under-Secretary of State
Thomas Pickering.
</P>
<P>
France has also expressed that it would encourage other EU
member countries to lift sanctions against Nigeria with its
progress in the democratization process.
</P>
<P>
The head of state has also reiterated the country's policy of
good neighborhood and appealed African leaders to solve conflicts
through peaceful means.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
