<HEADLINE> Singapore Stock Market Tumbles Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Share prices tumbled sharply on
the Singapore Stock Market Tuesday after the government projected
that total external trade for the whole year may shrink by 4.5-5.5
percent to reverse the four consecutive days of rally.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index (STII) fell by
39.80 points to close at 1062.52 points.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover slipped to 103.72 million shares worth
258.05 Singapore dollars (about 151.79 U.S. dollars). Falls
surged, outstripping rises by 240 to 29, while 321 stocks remained
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
TAC 200 was the most active stock as it registered a turnover
of 8.48 million units.
</P>
<P>
Elec&AMP;E topped the gainers of the day as it inched eight cents
to finish at 3.70 Singapore dollars. TAC 200 edged up eight cents
to 1.26 U.S. dollars at close. GP Bat was up six cents to close at
3.34 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 was the top loser of the day as it
lost 50 cents to end 20.90 Singapore dollars. SPH shed 50 cents to
finish at 11.90 Singapore dollars. SIA was next slipping by 40
cents to 6.30 Singapore dollars at finish.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the country's Trade Development Board (TDB) said in
a press release that the total trade in 1998 would decline by
between 4.5 to 5.5 percent after taking into account of the
decline in the first half of the year, the regional currency
crisis, the expected moderate growth in the United States, the
United Kingdom and Germany, the global oversupply of key
electronic products, the scaling down of operations by many
manufacturers in Singapore, the four-month slump in non-oil
imports as well as the continued weakness in oil trade.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the TDB comments about trade put a dampener
on the market and profit-taking on recent heavy gains set in
following the weak trade outlook projected by the government.
</P>
<P>
They also said that shares were compensating for gains that had
placed the market ahead of its regional counterparts in Asia in
the past few days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
