<HEADLINE> Commission of Inquiry on HK New Airport Set Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A Commission of Inquiry
appointed by the Chief Executive-in-Council has been formed here
Tuesday to probe into the operation of the new Hong Kong
International Airport which was opened on July 6 this year.
</P>
<P>
Justice Woo Kwok-hing has been appointed Chairman and Dr. Edgar
Cheng Wai-kin, former chairman of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, a
Commissioner.
</P>
<P>
The Commission is expected to finish its inquiry in around six
months and may call experts from local and overseas for
assistance.
</P>
<P>
It will have the following terms of reference:
</P>
<P>
-- To examine the planning and preparation for the opening of
the new airport including the adequacy of communication and
coordination between all interested parties;
</P>
<P>
-- To examine the decision to open the new airport on July 6,
1998 and the extent to which it was ready to begin operation on
that date;
</P>
<P>
-- To examine the operation of the new airport since it opened
on July 6, 1998 and to identify the roles of the various parties
involved;
</P>
<P>
-- To identify problems encountered in the operation of the new
airport and to establish their causes and where the responsibility
for each of them lies.
</P>
<P>
The terms of reference do not include maters to do with civil
liability or quantification of loss or damage.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, said: "the appointment of an independent
statutory commission demonstrates clearly our determination to
find out what went wrong, to establish where the responsibilities
lie, and to help prevent similar incidents from happening again."
</P>
<P>
"We have decided to appoint Mr. justice Woo Kwok-hing and Dr.
Edgar Cheng for their standing in the community and their record
of public service," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
