<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 75 Mln People Exposed to Arsenic Contamination in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 75 million people of
Bangladesh are at risk of arsenic contamination, according to
recent estimates by experts, who have asked the departments
concerned to take immediate steps to tackle the problem.
</P>
<P>
There are hardly any tubewells of the worst-affected 44
districts in the five southern regions of Bangladesh that are not
arsenic positive, the latest issue of the New Nation weekly quoted
a study as saying.
</P>
<P>
Conducted by the Disaster Forum, the study also said that
arsenic concentration in the ground water of the country's six
northeastern districts was alarming too.
</P>
<P>
Though there are different guidelines for maximum allowable
limit, the arsenic concentration level in both southern and
northeastern districts are well above the permitted level.
</P>
<P>
According to the United States Environment Agency, the maximum
permissible level is 0.03 mg (milligram)/liter, while the World
Health Organization and the Canadian guidelines put it at 0.05
mg/l.
</P>
<P>
Samples collected from 1,210 tubewells in the six districts
showed that the arsenic concentration level was between 0.05 and
0.10 mg/l.
</P>
<P>
About 96 percent of people living in the above-mentioned
districts depend on water pumped from the tubewells for their
survival.
</P>
<P>
The symptoms of arsenic toxicity may take 8-14 years to be
manifested in a person's body after the patient starts drinking
arsenic contaminated water, and the apparent symptoms of
arsenicosis may be said to have manifested themselves as melanosis
and keratosis mainly.
</P>
<P>
Up till now, altogether 60 districts out of the total of 64 in
the country with a population of 127 million are exposed to
arsenic contamination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Needs More Equipment to Fight Rebels: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
said here Tuesday morning that the army needs more equipment to
fight rebels in northern and western parts of his country.
</P>
<P>
The Uganda People's Defense Forces (UPDF) is presently lack of
more precise surveillance equipment to locate the rebels and this
is the first step towards wiping them out, he said.
</P>
<P>
The president also stressed the importance of the army's
mobility, saying that more helicopters and trucks are needed to
carry UPDF soldiers to the frontline.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Museveni accused the rebels of shunning
face-to-face confrontation with the government army and turning
their main energy to the soft targets.
</P>
<P>
They did this just to tarnish the image of the government and
prompt people to put more pressure on the government, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the UPDF has done a good job in the north in
spite of the lack of equipment.
</P>
<P>
The Lord Resistance Army took 800 rebels from southern Sudan
to northern Uganda and there were only 300 left two months before
it was forced to retreat to its base in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the letter he wrote to Kony recently,
Museveni said his letter meant to convey the message that the
government has not given up the possibility of resolving the
problem by peaceful means. 
</P>
</TEXT>
