<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Warring Parties Start Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The second round of Burundi
peace talks started Tuesday morning in Arusha, north Tanzania,
under the chairmanship of Tanzania's former president Julius
Nyerere.
</P>
<P>
Nineteen parties are taking part in the talks aimed at ending
a bitter ethnic conflict in which more than 150,000 people have
died since October 1993 in a series of bloody conflicts between
the Tutsi-dominated army and rebels who claimed to represent the
country's Hutu majority.
</P>
<P>
Two new parties, ANNADE and RADDES, also participated in the
second round of talks, which is expected to last more than two
weeks, with the participation of Burundian government officials
and the National Assembly, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Salim Ahmed Salim, secretary-general of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU), is also present at the talks.
</P>
<P>
The first task of Tuesday's meeting is to accept rules of a
procedure in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, who is the international mediator on Burundi peace
process, told the delegates in his opening remarks that other
issues to be tackled before the start of the face-to-face talks
between all warring parties are to discuss the root causes of
ethnic violence in Burundi and set up essential committees to end
crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
The peace facilitator has also proposed for election of
various chairmen of the sub-committees who could later meet to
suggest proposals of ending conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Supported by African leaders and the international community,
Nyerere began his mediation since August 1996 when seven east and
central African countries imposed economic sanctions on Bujumbura
following a military coup which toppled a civilian government led
by President Sylvestre Ntibantunganya and brought Major Pierre
Buyoya to power.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere has been holding informal meetings with various
parties in Arusha since Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The plenary session, which had been scheduled to start Monday,
was postponed to Tuesday following requests from the delegates to
be given more time to study rules of the procedure which was
issued Monday afternoon by the peace facilitator.
</P>
<P>
During the first round of negotiations in June the Burundian
government signed an agreement with three rebel groups and 12
political parties to return to the negotiating table and
implement a cease-fire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
