<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar lifted
almost half a U.S. cent Tuesday as the Japanese foreign exchange
market returned from holidays to provide some spark for the local
unit.
</P>
<P>
After Monday dropping by almost one U.S. cent in the absence of
Japanese traders, the Australian dollar Tuesday confirmed its
close relationship with the yen as they rose together.
</P>
<P>
At the close, the Australian dollar was changing hands at 62.93
U.S. cents from 62.45 late Monday.
</P>
<P>
An attempt to hold above 63 U.S. cents did not last and IBJ
Australia senior foreign exchange trader Darrin Stewart said the
currency was largely trading at the higher level ahead of key
domestic data and the expected announcement of a new Japanese
prime minister on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Swift and decisive action on economic reform to lift Japan's
moribund economy by the new prime minister would underpin support
for the yen, and in turn, the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the domestic unit was buying 87.57 Japanese
yen from 87.04 Monday and 1.1216 German marks from 1.1123.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market had surrendered to a "wait and see"
mentality ahead of an address by U.S. Federal Reserve chairman
Alan Greenspan to the Congress tonight along with the inflation
figures.
</P>
<P>
"The market has been active in terms of volume, performing a
little bit better than the last day or so, but we have really gone
nowhere," ANZ Investment Bank head of securities trading Jeremy
Colless said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics' inflation data due
Wednesday is widely expected to be "market friendly", with
economists predicting a rise of 0.5 percent in both the consumer
price index and the treasury's underlying rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
