<HEADLINE> Australian Sharemarkets Close Steady </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares ended flat in
quiet trade Tuesday after an afternoon sell off in industrials
offset a better performance by resources, particularly gold
stocks.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index ended flat at 2787.9, all industrials
lost 4.8 points to 4882.2 and all resources gained 4.5 to 1099.7.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said demand for industrial stocks softened over the day
ahead of U.S. Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan's address to
Congress Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
"There was a bit of balance squaring (this afternoon) ahead of
Greenspan's speech tonight ... and that knocked the earlier gains
on the head a bit," Dicksons broker Jon Hancock said.
</P>
<P>
"And the fact the Dow (Jones Industrial Average) drifted last
night only added to the caution."
</P>
<P>
The key U.S. index lost 42.2 points overnight to 9295.8.
</P>
<P>
Overall local volume traded at the close was a relatively small
254.7 million shares worth 740.1 million Australian dollars
(466.26 million U.S. dollars), with falling stocks just higher
than rising stocks at 491 versus 488.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector the gold subindex's rise of 2.66
percent (29.4 points) to 1134.4.
</P>
<P>
Two of the stronger gainers in resources were North, up 12, and
WMC, up seven cents.
</P>
<P>
Leader BHP ended three cents stronger while global rival Rio
Tinto retreated 13.3.
</P>
<P>
Among the major industrials the picture was less rosy as most
major stocks ended lower or only marginally higher.
</P>
<P>
News Corp gained two cents and its preferred shares were steady
at 11.70 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Telco giant Telstra drifted four cents but AMP gained 9.4.
</P>
<P>
Major banking stocks all ended lower. ANZ slipped seven,
Commonwealth gave up three, National Australia eased 16 and
Westpac's lost 4.8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
