<HEADLINE> U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Arrives in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott arrived here Tuesday afternoon for a two-day visit
to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Talbott, who flew into here from New Delhi, was greeted by
Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad at the Islamabad
airport.
</P>
<P>
Talbott, who is leading a high-level U.S. delegation, will hold
talks with Shamshad late Tuesday afternoon and he will call on
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Talbott will discuss with the Pakistani
leadership the current situation in South Asia and he will spell
out Washington's stance on various issues in the region with
particular reference to its non-proliferation objectives.
</P>
<P>
Talbott's visit took place a few days after the Clinton
Administration got broad authority to temporarily lift all
economic sanctions against Pakistan and India imposed following
their nuclear tests in May.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has also softened its position for signing the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty and Nuclear Non-proliferation
Treaty.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Office spokesman said on Saturday that Pakistan was
no longer linking the signing of these accords with that of India.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
