<HEADLINE> Three Politicians File Candidacy in LDP Presidential Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo
Obuchi, former Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama and Health
and Welfare Minister Junichiro Koizumi on Tuesday filed their
candidacy for presidency of Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic
Party (LDP).
</P>
<P>
The three candidates, speaking at a joint news conference
shortly after filing their candidacy, reiterated their campaign
promises to revitalize the sluggish Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
"Now is the time to make decisions" to ride out the recession
and settle the bad-loan problems of Japanese banks, said Kajiyama,
72, the oldest among the three hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
"I will tackle the bad-loan problem" even if it means "putting
my life at risk," said Kajiyama, who is supported by some business
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, 61, vowed to form "the most powerful cabinet" if
elected and to proceed to conclude a peace treaty with Russia by
2000. He is backed by the largest faction within the LDP.
</P>
<P>
Koizumi, 56, who is favored by many of the LDP's younger
lawmakers, promised to make Japan a reliable democratic country
with an internationally acceptable economic structure.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto tendered his
resignation July 13 as LDP leader to take responsibility for the
party's major setback in the July 12 House of Councillors (upper
house) election.
</P>
<P>
A total of 413 LDP parliamentarians and local-chapter
representatives will vote Friday to pick the successor to
Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
The new LDP president is sure to take the helm of the Japanese
government as the LDP holds a majority in the House of
Representatives (lower house), which has the final say in the
selection of a prime minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
