<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Say China's Yellow River Could Dry Up By 2020 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese water conservation
specialists are predicting that China's second longest river, the
Yellow River, could be dry up year round at its lower reaches by
the year 2020 as a result of drought, "China Youth News" reports
today.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River started suffering from dry spells in the early
1970s and it has dried up 18 times over the past 25 years, with
each dry spell averaging for a week. In 1997, the dry-up period on
the lower reaches of the river lasted 226 days.
</P>
<P>
Based on these data, scientists say the river's dry spells will
lengthen to 140 days by the year 2000 and to 200 days by 2010.
</P>
<P>
This will have an adverse effect on development and on people's
livelihoods in those areas as the water table drops, the climate
gets drier, and desertification starts on some river courses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dengue Fever Claims 120 Lives in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Dengue fever has claimed 120 lives
in Vietnam in the first six months of this year, five times more
than in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
As declared in the latest issue of the Vietnam Investment
Review, health authorities recorded a total of 46,373 cases of the
disease during this period, nearly three times more than in the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The disease is transmitted by mosquitos and causes fever and
hemorrhage.
</P>
<P>
Forty-two out of 61 provinces throughout the country, specially
the coastal provinces in southern and central Vietnam, have
reported cases of dengue fever infection over the past six months.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the disease claimed 224 lives
in 1997, an alarming 13.5 percent increase over 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
