<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clearer Skies For Northwestern China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The skies over Lanzhou, the
capital of northwest China's Gansu Province, are clear again
thanks to the government's "blue sky" program.
</P>
<P>
Lanzhou suffered from serious environmental pollution caused by
the burning of coal, which made the city's sky gray all year
round, so it began the "blue sky" program in 1994, spending 1.45
billion yuan (180 million U.S. dollars) on combating atmospheric
pollution.
</P>
<P>
Trees have been planted on 6,600 hectares of ground around the
city and 32 environmental monitoring stations set up, and 38
industrial waste gas sites.
</P>
<P>
The city has built 146 pollution treatment projects and its
suspended particle index has dropped to 0.74 mg per cubic meter
from 1.07 mg per cubic meter.
</P>
<P>
Many residents leave their homes to have a look at the blue
sky, which was just a distant memory for most of them. "I've
seldom seen such blue skies my whole life," said Wang Chengzhi, a
70-year-old man who was standing on the dyke of the Yellow River,
staring up at the sky.
</P>
<P>
The city government has stepped up environmental protection,
replacing coal with electricity as its major energy source,
providing a fundamental solution to the environmental pollution
problem, a leading city government official told reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Launches Ultraviolet Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 21 (Xinhua) - During the intensely hot summer, a
new weather service for ultraviolet ray forecasts has begun in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The new service gives ultraviolet ray intensity at noon every
day and describes the ways it can harm people's skin and reminds
people to wear hats in the scorching sun and avoid going outside
from 10:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m.
</P>
<P>
Ultraviolet rays are good for people's health but too much
exposure can cause burns, cancer, or eye diseases, according to
Shao Demin, of the Shanghai Meteorology Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
The institute has made pollution and ultraviolet rays the key
focus of their research this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
