<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Promises to Modernize Electoral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
has assured the public that the full computerization of the
electoral process will become a reality under his administration,
in time for the next national and local polls in the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
The modernization of the country's antiquated poll system,
which failed to materialize during the previous administration,
will be a priority during the first 100 days of the Estrada
presidency, the Presidential Press Office said Tuesday in a press
release.
</P>
<P>
"This time I'll do it. I am committed to do it and we'll start
the modernization of the electoral process," Estrada was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Aside from full computerization, Estrada's 100 Days People's
Priority Agenda also includes measures to lift the political
advertisement ban, impose ban on political dynasties and enable
overseas Filipinos to vote.
</P>
<P>
The move to computerize vote counting will lead to the early
proclamation of winners, making the tampering of election results
more difficult for cheaters.
</P>
<P>
The full modernization of the electoral system will be
complemented by the creation of a presidential commission on
constitutional reforms to study proposed amendments to the
Constitution, a move that will ensure that the government remains
"transparent, consultative and responsive" to the needs of the
majority.
</P>
<P>
Congress passed a law on poll computerization last December,
but the lack of time prevented the Commission on Elections from
implementing it on a nationwide basis during the May 11
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
The Autonomous Region for Muslim Mindanao, which had
computerized elections in 1995, was the only beneficiary of the
poll modernization measure during the May 11 polls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
