<HEADLINE> International Language Villages In Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S.'s Concordia Language
Village has opened branches in the Chinese cities of Ningbo,
Jinan, Hangzhou and Changchun.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 800 Chinese students have been enrolled in the villages
where they are being taught by some 73 American teachers.
</P>
<P>
The villages provides courses in English on language,
literature, music, sports, fine arts and games.
</P>
<P>
The Concordia Language Village was established in 1961 by
Dr. Gerry Haukebo. The village covers 11 languages and has an
average enrollment of 8,000 students every year.
</P>
<P>
The first village in China was set up last year in Ningbo in
east China's Zhejiang Province. 
</P>
