<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Govt, Unions Urged to Hold Dialog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean government and the
Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions (ZCTU) have been urged to
continue dialog to resolve their differences.
</P>
<P>
The country's leading daily Herald said Tuesday that state and
the ZCTU should continue with dialog.
</P>
<P>
ZCTU Secretary General Morgan Tsvangirai said Monday the ZCTU
still had the option to call for another nationwide work boycott
and it could not rule out the mass national strike when it has
not even met its demands.
</P>
<P>
The ZCTU organized a mass job stay-away in January this year
which crippled the country's economy, resulting in the loss of
business worth more than 3.8 million U.S. Dollars over two days.
</P>
<P>
The strike forced the government into accepting some of its
demands, which include scrapping the five percent development
levy, tax on pensions and the need for the government to find a
long term solution to high increases of basic commodities.
</P>
<P>
"What is important is for all stake-holders to work together
to solve the country's economic problems," said a commentary
carried in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
If the ZCTU is truly interested in the workers' welfare,
rather than advancing the political careers of individual
leaders, it should continue seeking dialog with the government
and seek ways to advance to what must be the real goal: a better
standard of living and a higher quality of life for the ordinary
worker, said the commentary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
