<HEADLINE> ADB Grants for Kenya's Health Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The African Development Bank
(ADB) has issued a loan worth 672 million Shillings (around 11
million U.S. Dollars) to help deepen health reforms and improve
primary health care services in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
This is the second credit in the Kenyan health sector extended
by the bank following the one extended in 1986 to finance rural
health project, which has been completed, media reports here said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Omar Kabbaj, president of the bank, lauded the ongoing reform
in Kenya's health sector Monday when signing the loan agreement
with Kenyan Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae.
</P>
<P>
Kabbaj said the Kenyan government had demonstrated the
determination to promote and ensure equitable distribution of
basic health care services.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Health Policy Framework was in line with ADB's own
policies, as it's placing emphasis on the reduction in the rate
of construction of new government health facilities and focusing
instead, on rehabilitating and properly maintaining existing
ones, he said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB money, said Nyachae, will finance the rehabilitation
and upgrading of health facilities in seven districts under the
Rural Health Project II Program.
</P>
<P>
"The objective (of the credit) is to improve the health status
of the target communities through a primary health care strategy,
with a focus on community participation and support to community
initiative," said Nyachae. 
</P>
