<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Politicians to Comment on AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Advocacy for prevention and
control of the spread of HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, is set
to take on a new face in Zimbabwe with the highest political
level pledging to use every platform to talk about the pandemic.
</P>
<P>
Vice-President Simon Muzenda Monday pledged to a high level
political delegation that recently visited Uganda that he was
ready to be among the senior politicians who will openly speak
about AIDS, the daily Herald reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"There is no way we can run away from this problem. We cannot
just brush it aside especially after realizing what the pandemic
is doing to our productive young men and women," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Putting a cover around AIDS has been our biggest weakness,"
Muzenda told the delegation.
</P>
<P>
The 12-member delegation was in Uganda for a week studying how
that country had succeeded in bringing down HIV infection levels.
</P>
<P>
Muzenda said it was unfortunate that Zimbabwe, which together
with Botswana are leading the world in having the highest numbers
of HIV infected people, was not "very active" in trying to
prevent and control further infection.
</P>
<P>
Head of the delegation, Minister of State in President's
Office Oppah Muchinguri said among the important lessons learned
was that there was urgent need for the country to adopt an open
minded attitude about AIDS.
</P>
<P>
She said another important lesson learned was the highest
political office's involvement in advocacy for AIDS prevention
and control strategies.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.5 million Zimbabweans are estimated to be infected
with HIV. This means that one in every four people has the HIV
virus.
</P>
<P>
Uganda, which in the late 80s had infection levels at 30
percent, has managed to reduce it to 12.8 percent at present.
</P>
</TEXT>
