<HEADLINE> Chinese President Emphasizes Ties With Japan's Communist Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin, General
Secretary of the Communist Party of China Central Committee, in a
meeting here today with Japanese communists, said that the CPC
will develop a new type of party-to-party relationship with the
Communist Party of Japan under principles confirmed by the two
parties.
</P>
<P>
Jiang told the delegation, which was led by Tetsuzo Fuwa,
chairman of the Presidium of the CPJ Central Committee, that the
CPC will reinforce ties with the JPC to contribute to an
understanding between the Chinese and Japanese and to establish
long-term, stable and good-neighborly Sino-Japanese relations
geared to the next century.
</P>
<P>
The CPC and CPJ announced the normalization of party-to-party
relations last month. They had severed ties in the 1960s, during
China's "Cultural Revolution."
</P>
<P>
Jiang congratulated them on the normalization of relations and
said that it is an important event, and added that this year is
the 20th anniversary of the signing of the Sino-Japanese Treaty of
Peace and Friendship and that the two countries have reached an
important historic period of inheriting the past and ushering in
the future.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is in the interest of their people and the
peace, stability and development of the Asia-Pacific region and
the entire world if China and Japan, two major nations in Asia and
in the world, have good-neighborly and friendly relations,
increase mutually-beneficial cooperation, and prolong their
friendship for generations.
</P>
<P>
Fuwa said that since Japan and China normalized relations in
1972 there has been development in bilateral ties and the
normalization of CPJ and CPC relations fits this trend.
</P>
<P>
He also spoke about the development of Japan-China ties and
told Jiang that the CPJ is ready to work with the CPC for the
growth of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also discussed China's reform and opening to the outside
world and the country's foreign relations.
</P>
<P>
The CPJ delegation arrived here Sunday at the invitation of
the CPC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
