<HEADLINE> Judiciary Plays Vital Role: Tembo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Vice-President Christon
Tembo has said the judiciary plays a pivotal role in governance
as a major watchdog over all other state organs.
</P>
<P>
Speaking Monday in Livingstone, Zambia's tourist capital in
the southern border, while officially opening a Judges seminar on
"Enhancing Knowledge for Effective Justice Delivery", Tembo said
the judiciary is a traditional custodian of law, freedom and
human rights.
</P>
<P>
It is imperative that the nation has an efficient
knowledgeable and professional judiciary that will be the
protector of individual rights as well, he was quoted by Zambia
Daily Mail Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tembo added that the services rendered by Judges could not be
assured by monetary means but demand the highest facilities of
learning, training and character.
</P>
<P>
Judges status should not be regarded as power symbols as it is
a mark of high social and professional responsibility, said Tembo
while noting that Judges do not enjoy political leadership or
power over life and death, punishment and mercy.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president also stressed that the judiciary is one of
the chief anchors of democracy, hence the need for accountability
and transparency in their dealings and practices.
</P>
<P>
The seminor is held when the magistrates' strike throughout
Zambia has entered the third week, leaving the courts deserted
and cases piling up.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian magistrates have been demanding better salaries
and servicing conditions but up till now there is no response
from the government. 
</P>
