<HEADLINE> Chinese Prosecutors Getting Corruption Reports At Street Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) - More than 100,000 prosecutors in
China took to the streets today in cities and villages to give
legal advice to the public about reporting corruption.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang Qiong, deputy procurator-general of the
Supreme People's Procuratorate, most of today's complaints were
about village leaders and township officials.
</P>
<P>
Many villagers came to Beijing to report about township and
village officials illegally diverting public funds, Zhang said,
from his position on Wangfujing Street in downtown Beijing. Others
reported that local leaders levied improper taxes, he said.
</P>
<P>
This consultation service for the pubic about reporting on
corruption was started by the country's 37,000 prosecutors offices
as part of the 10th anniversary of reporting on corruption in
China.
</P>
<P>
The deputy procurator-general said that today's activities were
also meant to inform the public about the responsibilities of
prosecutors and that this makes it easier for the public to report
crimes to the authorities and to have their legal problems
addressed, Zhang said.  
</P>
