<HEADLINE> Foreign Exchange Inflows into Zambia Static </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The inflow of foreign currency has
remained at zero with no donor inflows coming into the Bank of
Zambia since March, and Zambia has continued debts servicing thus
depleting international reserves.
</P>
<P>
The latest Bank of Zambia Fortnight Statistics for the week
ending June 26 reaching here Tuesday shows that Zambia's reserves
have remained at 155 million U.S. Dollars since March this year
and yet the country has been disbursed money to meet debt
obligations.
</P>
<P>
At least seven million Dollars was paid out in debt servicing
in April and yet there are no inflows during the same period.
There were other outflows for debt servicing of about 4.7 million
Dollars without any donor inflows.
</P>
<P>
Since March, there has been no significant inflows of foreign
currency from donors who have indicated that they will not
release any Balance of Payment support until after the sale of
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM), the country's largest
foreign exchange earner.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank has not bought any foreign currency in the
past four months from ZCCM which has in some cases been selling
foreign currency straight to the market.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Central Bank paid out almost 13.5 million
Dollars in debt servicing in June although during this period,
there were some inflows amounting to three million Dollars from
other non-governmental inflows, with none from ZCCM and donors.
</P>
</TEXT>
