<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Former captain and goalkeeper Dino
Zoff will replace Cesare Maldini as coach of the Italian national
soccer squad this week, said ANSA news agency on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Luciano Nizzola, president of the Italian Football Federation,
had secret talks with Maldini in Turin on Monday and would return
to Rome on Tuesday to meet Zoff, ANSA said.
</P>
<P>
And the decision would probably be announced before meetings of
the Italian Olympic Committee CONI and the Football League, both
of which are scheduled for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Cesare Maldini's career as Italy coach is over and Dino Zoff's
is about to begin," ANSA said.
</P>
<P>
With his contract runs to the end of 1998, Maldini hoped to see
it out despite criticism for Italy's poor show in the World Cup
finals wherein they were beaten by France in the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
Zoff, who also run for the coach's job when Maldini replaced
Arrigo Sacchi in late 1996, is the current president of Lazio.
</P>
<P>
Being captain, Zoff enjoys high reputation in Italy as its
squad won the 1982 World Cup finals in Spain.
</P>
<P>
Zoff is also the most capped Italian of all time, having played
112 times for his country. 
