<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Made Drug May Beat Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Cancer patients may soon be
spared the
agony of chemotherapy, thanks to a drug developed by New Zealand
researchers.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent report of the Auckland-based newspaper
The New
Zealand Herald, Auckland University's Cancer Society Research
Center
headed by Professor Bill Denny has developed a chemical to fight
breast
and ovarian cancer with almost no side-effects.
</P>
<P>
If trials are successful, the treatment could be available in
two
years and is likely to be taken orally.
</P>
<P>
Until now, chemotherapy has been the only way of tackling
cancer,
bringing with it unfortunate side-effects such as hair loss and
lowered
resistance to infection.
</P>
<P>
But the new compound, EGFR, could end the suffering by shutting
down
abnormally functioning cells rather than wiping them out.
</P>
<P>
Parke-Davis, a US drug company working with the Auckland
researchers,
was so impressed with initial results that it agreed to begin
clinical
trials.
</P>
<P>
Professor Denny said: "If the trials prove successful it will
hopefully offer cancer patients a far less traumatic form of
treatment."
</P>
<P>
He said that the drug worked by targeting the signaling
pathways by
which cells communicate. In cancer cases, the enzyme components of
these
pathways mutate and produce irregular tumor-forming cells.
</P>
<P>
"One of the most important enzymes in the human body is called
epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR) which is responsible for
wound
healing."
</P>
<P>
The enzyme sits on the cell surface and acts like a trigger,
telling
the cells when to divide to heal wounds. Normally, once the injury
has
healed, the enzyme switches off and the cells stop dividing.
</P>
<P>
But in many human lung, ovarian and breast tumors the enzyme
tells the
cells to keep on dividing, leading to cancerous tumors.
</P>
<P>
The new drug works by selectively blocking the function of
EGFR,
preventing it from sending growth signals to the cell nucleus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
