<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Poverty Level Widens: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- About 13 million Kenyans are
living in absolute poverty and the number will swell in the
coming years if economic growth still stagnates, according to a
Central Bureau of Statistics (CBS) report.
</P>
<P>
Half of the families in the east African state has serious
food problems, the East African Standard newspaper quoted the
report as saying.
</P>
<P>
Intensity of poverty is much worse in arid and semi-arid
areas, urban slums as well as among female-headed households,
said the report, the first of this kind issued by the Kenyan
government.
</P>
<P>
The pattern of poverty shows that 47 percent of Kenyans living
in rural areas are poor. The figure in urban areas stands at 29
percent.
</P>
<P>
The report classified four out of all the eight provinces --
Eastern, Western, Coast and North Eastern -- as "very poor
provinces."
</P>
<P>
At least 25 percent of victims of poverty in the country are
in Eastern Province, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The glimpse of urban poverty shows that 44 percent of
residents in Kisumu and Nakuru, Kenya's third and fourth largest
cities, suffer from absolute poverty.
</P>
<P>
One fourth of the people in capital Nairobi and almost one
third of residents in the Indian Ocean port of Mombasa, Kenya's
second largest city, are poor.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 18 percent of Kenya's population is composed of
urban dwellers of which 60 percent live in Nairobi, Mombasa,
Kisumu and Nakuru.
</P>
<P>
Whereas there is no official poverty line in Kenya, CBS
researchers defined poverty as a multi-dimensional phenomenon
that specifies levels of deprivation of basic needs.
</P>
<P>
In order to derive a poverty line for Kenya, researchers used
U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization minimum recommended daily
allowance of 2,250 calories per person.
</P>
<P>
The researchers thus set food poverty line expenditure at 978
Shillings (about 16.5 U.S. Dollars) in rural areas and 1,490
Shillings (25 Dollars) in urban areas per month.
</P>
<P>
"This means that it takes about 70 percent more to survive in
urban areas than up country," says the report.
</P>
<P>
The researchers estimated that the country needs 41 billion
Shillings (689 million Dollars) in fighting against poverty in
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
"Low investment and inefficient parastatal sector has led to a
fall in real wages, doubling unemployment and ringering
rural-urban migration," says the report.
</P>
<P>
Lack of ownership and access to land has become a major cause
for poverty among women who comprise 50.2 percent of Kenya's
population of estimated nearly 30 million.
</P>
<P>
Other dominant causes for poverty in Kenya include illiteracy,
negative cultural attitudes and practices, according to the
report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Gov't to Dispose Stakes in Private Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
planning to dispose its stakes in private banks, particularly the
Philippine National Bank (PNB), within a year, the Department of
Finance said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Felicitas del Rosario, spokesperson for the department, said
that the move was not just true with the PNB but the rest of
government-controlled corporations where the government has
interests.
</P>
<P>
She added that this move is in line with President Joseph
Estrada's directive to privatize government assets and
government-controlled corporations, particularly those not doing
well in their operations.
</P>
<P>
But del Rosario explained that prior to the disposition of
these stakes, the Finance Department will conduct a thorough study
and evaluation to determine how much really is needed to offset
the government's budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
The government, which suffered 24 billion pesos (0.585 billion
U.S. dollars) in budget deficit for the first half of the year, is
expected to incur a staggering deficit of more than 50 billion
pesos (1.22 billion dollars) for the entire 1998, according to the
Department of Budget and Management.
</P>
<P>
The Estrada administration has listed privatization of state
assets as one way to make up the ballooning deficit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
