<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 237,000 Zimbabweans Drop out of School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- More than 237,000 Zimbabwean
pupils dropped out of school countrywide last year because of
financial problems, long distances between schools and homes and
lack of confidence in the future.
</P>
<P>
Officials in the Ministry of Education, Sport and Culture
Monday attributed the high number of school drop-outs to levies,
distances which the pupils have to travel, and the high rate of
unemployment, the daily Herald reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Of the 237,000 pupils who dropped out of school, 105,000 were
in primary school. Drop-outs were registered from as early as
Grade One.
</P>
<P>
Distances which the pupils travel to the nearest school have
been cited as one of the major reasons for dropping out at Grade
One level. In some rural communities, pupils walk up to 20 km to
and from the nearest school.
</P>
<P>
The government built a number of primary and secondary schools
soon after independence in 1980 in an effort to provide basic
education to pupils who had been disadvantaged because of the
country's colonial past.
</P>
<P>
There are over 6,000 primary and secondary schools countrywide
but more are needed if distances to be travelled are to be
reduced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
