<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Muluzi Calls for Curriculum Review to Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Malawian President Bakili Muluzi
has called for a continuous review of the country's education
curriculum to "meet the needs of the society."
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the national radio Malawi Broadcasting Corporation
(MBC) to mark the "National Day of Education" that fell on
Sunday, Muluzi said there is need to identify the society's needs
and see whether or not the current curriculum address those
needs, the Malawi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The needs of the society are as dynamic as the society
itself," he said, adding, "it is very important that the review
of our curriculum should be an ongoing process if we are to
maintain quality education."
</P>
<P>
He lashed out at private school owners who use unsuitable
premises, few and under-qualified teachers in their schools,
urging them to give pupils education worth the "value to their
money."
</P>
<P>
Since Malawi attained multi-party democracy in 1994, there has
been an upsurge in both primary and secondary private schools,
most of which have been condemned by people as sub-standard and
not conducive to better learning though they charge exorbitant
fees.
</P>
<P>
"It is only fair that private schools charge affordable and
reasonable fees. They should not exploit desperate students and
parents," said Muluzi.
</P>
<P>
"Quality education is inevitably dependent on the quality of
both teachers and pupils," he said.
</P>
<P>
To improve on the country's education by allowing more pupils
in schools, Muluzi's administration introduced free primary
education in 1994 which has soared enrollment from 1.9 million to
3.2 million.
</P>
<P>
However, the president stressed the need to have
well-qualified and motivated teachers in primary and secondary
schools as well as colleges and distance education centers.
</P>
<P>
To this effect, over 10,000 primary school teachers are
currently undergoing training under the "Malawi integrated
teachers program".
</P>
<P>
With some 20,000 teachers already recruited for the free
primary education, the teacher-pupil ratio has now improved to
1:60 in most Malawian schools against the 1:120 ratio before
1994.
</P>
<P>
Malawian government has opened a new university, Mzuzu
University and increased enrollment in existing teachers'
colleges to train more teachers.
</P>
<P>
A total of 315 primary education advisors (PEAs) have been
assigned by the government to monitor primary and secondary
schools in the country's 315 education zones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
