<HEADLINE> Southern China Cracking Down on Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, July 21 (Xinhua) -- China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region seized 22.7 million yuan (about 2.7 million U.S. dollars)
worth of smuggled goods in the first five months of 1998, which
included 112 cars and 3,490 boxes of cigarettes, according to the
regional government.
</P>
<P>
The region has a 1,020-km border and 1,595 km of coastline, an
ideal area for smugglers, but its Vice-chairman Zhang Wenxue
attributes the success in the anti-smuggling drive to joint
efforts of various departments.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the Public Security Department, Customs, industrial
and commercial administrations, and other departments have
cooperated in dealing with the smuggling problem by keeping a
close eye on major transportation lines, and ports and bays.
</P>
</TEXT>
