<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two U.N. Employees Killed in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Two Afghan men working with the
United Nations aid agencies who were abducted on July 13 in
Jalalabad, Afghanistan, were found dead over the weekend, a U.N.
spokeswoman here confirmed on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Bahsaryar, 55, a clerk with the World Food Program, and
Mohamed Nuri Habibi, 49, a program assistant with the United
Nations High Commission for Refugees, were taken by unidentified
men while on their way to work, according to a press release
issued by acting U.N. spokeswoman Susan Manuel.
</P>
<P>
U.N. officials reported the disappearances to the Taliban
officials including the governor of Nangahar province, located in
eastern Afghanistan close to the border of Pakistan, she said in
the release,
</P>
<P>
Local authorities last week told the U.N. they were
investigating the case, but confirmed that the two men had not
been arrested, she added.
</P>
<P>
The body of Basharyar was found Saturday in a river in Beshud
district west of Kabul, while Habibi's body was found Sunday in a
river in Lalpur district east of Jalalabad, she said. However, no
motive has been determined for the killing.
</P>
<P>
The office of the U.N. Humanitarian Coordinator for
Afghanistan, based in Islamabad, Pakistan, had written to the
Taliban authorities demanding a full investigation into the
deaths, the U.N. official said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. officials also called on the authorities to provide closer
security to U.N. staff in Afghanistan, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
