<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalian Grows Into Popular Tourist Destination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Dalian, a coastal resort in
northeast China's Liaoning Province, has developed into a popular
tourist destination thanks to the introduction of the city's
diverse special tourism programs.
</P>
<P>
Special tourism activities feature Chinese scholar trees in
spring, commodity trade fairs in summer, garment festivals and
international marathon races in autumn, and fireworks and ice
lantern festivals in winter.
</P>
<P>
The programs provide year-round entertainment for tourists,
according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
The city hosted 18 million tourists last year, with earnings
for the year standing at 5.1 billion yuan. The over 200,000
foreign tourists spent over 200 million U.S. dollars in Dalian.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Fluon Plant Operational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 21 (Xinhua) -- China's largest-ever plant to
produce polytetrafluoroethylene, known as the "king of plastics,"
have gone into operation in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The plant, a Sino-Russian joint venture, was designed to
have an annual production capacity of 3,000 tons and was built at
a cost of 300 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Because this product is antiplastering and resistant to dirt
and corrosion, it is now widely used in aviation, machinery,
chemistry, the military and emergency medical treatment. China
presently imports thousands of tons of polytetrafluoroethylene
annually.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Makes Economic Achievements Despite Difficulties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Despite great difficulties, Vietnam
has made considerable economic achievements, said Vietnam Prime
Minister Phan Van Khai, according to Vietnamese media here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Khai said this at the national conference on economy here on
July 19 and 20, which was attended by senior government officials
and state-run corporation directors.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said though facing great difficulties and
complicated developments in the midst of Asian financial crisis,
Vietnam kept its gross domestic product (GDP) growth at 6.62
percent.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of 1998, Vietnam's agricultural and
industrial output value increased 2 percent and 12.6 percent
respectively, while export turnover grew 9.2 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Macro-economy and socio-political situation remain basically
good, Khai stressed.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the achievements to the timely and proper
policies initiated by the government, adding that the
policies were in conformity with the aspiration of the people,
therefore helped mobilize internal resources of the whole nation.
</P>
<P>
However, Khai warned of greater difficulties in the second half
of 1998 and early 1999, urging the people to continue coping with
great challenges caused by natural calamities and the on-going
regional financial fallout, particularly weaknesses and
shortcomings of the economy itself. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Hauls Six Golds on Day Two of Goodwill Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Russia is leading the gold war
against the United States after winning six more gold medals on
the second day of the Goodwill Games here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Russia claimed four titles in athletics competition, and added
two more from the synchronized swimming. The United States raked
up five golds from track and field to boost its title tally to 10,
one short of Russia's 11.
</P>
<P>
In today's competition, Kenya snatched two titles and Cuba won
the rest one at the Nassau County's Mitchel athletics complex,
while Beralus got a top laural from the gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
Four meet records fell in the final-only format athletics
competition, and China's world record holder Jiang Bo put up a
disastrous performance in the women's 5,000 meters by wrapping up
last.
</P>
<P>
Marion Jones of the United States swept a sprint double with a
win in the women's 200 meters in a meet record-breaking time of
21.80 seconds, beating the previous record of 22.09. The world
fastest woman won the 100 meters yesterday, also beating the meet
record.
</P>
<P>
U.S. world record holder Dan O'Brien collected a total of 8,755
points to win the men's decathlon, narrowly missing the world
record but good enough to beat the previous meet mark of 8,715.
</P>
<P>
Mark Crear gave the local crowd something to cheer when he
clocked 13.06 seconds in the men's 110-meter hurdles, knocking off
the meet record of 13.25 and beating world champion Allen Johnson
ofthe United States into second place. Briton world record holder
Colin Jackson wound up fourth.
</P>
<P>
Tisha Waller of the United States jumped over 1.97 meters to
win the women's high jump gold, and Angela Vaughn rounded up the
fifth title for the host by claiming the women's 100-meter hurdles
in 12.72 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Cuba's world champion Ivan Pedroso long jumped 8.54 meters to
underline his superiority in the event, beating Erick Walder of
the United States and James Beckford of Jamaica, who landed at
8.38 and 8.34.
</P>
<P>
"It was a good competition, the field was very strong,"
Pedrososaid after his triumph.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's world record holder Bernard Barmasai set a new meet
record in the men's 3,000-meter steeplechase with a time of
8:14.26, 0.04 seconds inside the old mark. Three-time world
champion Moses Kiptanui didn't finish the race.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Ndururi won another gold for Kenya by returning home
first in the men's 800 meters in 1:45.30, 0.20 seconds slower than
the meet record.
</P>
<P>
Russia's Olga Yegorova chalked up the women's 5,000 meters
title in a slow time of 15:53.05, followed by Libbie Hickman of
the United States and Lyubov Kremlyova of Russia.
</P>
<P>
China's Ma's Army runners Jiang Bo and Dong Yanmei, world
record beating runners last year in Shanghai, disappointed the
crowd here when they finished eighth and fourth respectively.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who set the world record 14:28.09 last October, followed
the two leading Russians in the third position most of the time,
with Dong, world number two last year, setting fourth.
</P>
<P>
Dong, who couldn't match up Yegorova's tremendous final kick,
cruised home in 16:00.56, more than one minute and half slower
than her personal best. Jiang, who never surged to the lead and
faded away from the first group with 400 meters to go.
</P>
<P>
Natalya Sadova tossed the plate to 65.80 meters to win the
women's discus, beating Olympic champion Ilke Wyludda of Germany
into second position.
</P>
<P>
Svetlana Masterkova and Ilya Markov won the other two golds for
Russia from the women's mile and men's 20km walk.
</P>
<P>
Ivan Ivankov of Belarus scored a total of 57.500 points to win
the men's all-around gold in gymnastics, the first gold for his
country at the current Games. Alexei Bondarenko of Russia and
Blaine Wilson of the United States wrapped up second and third.
</P>
<P>
Russia edged the United States in the synchronized swimming
team event, collecting 98.774 points to the host's 97.943. A
Russian pair Olga Brousnikina and Maria Kisseleva displayed a
brilliant show in the synchronized swimming duet event, accounting
for a total of 99.016 points. The United States won the silver
with 97.979.
</P>
<P>
In today's basketball preliminary rounds, the United States
beat China 91-76, Lithuania defeated Argentina 81-77, Brazil
downed defending champions Puerto Rico 96-92, and Russia hammered
Australia 81-73. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Caldwell Ousts Carlsen at Legg Mason Classic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 20 (Xinhua) -- David Caldwell pulled a big
upset by beating 13th-seeded Kenneth Carlsen of Denmark in the
opening round of the Legg Mason Classic on Monday.
</P>
<P>
American Caldwell, who had never won an ATP Tour match,
defeated Carlsen 3-6, 6-4, 7-5 in the sweltering heat.
</P>
<P>
Caldwell, who turned pro in 1996 and ranked 245th in the world,
had to win two qualifiers over the weekend to get into the
tournament. He avoided a third-set tiebreaker by winning the final
10 points of the match.
</P>
<P>
In other action of the day, Paul Goldstein failed to shine in
his professional debut, losing to Sargis Sargsian of Armenia 3-6,
6-4, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
Gianluca Pozzi of Italy, the 11th seed, and 15th-seeded Martin
Damm of the Czech Republic both advanced in the tournament while
Daniel Nestor of Canada ousted 16th-seeded Daniel Vacek of the
Czech Republic 6-4, 6-4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
