<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Lift Ban on Gas Additive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government said on
Monday that it would lift immediately its year-old ban on the
gasoline additive MMT.
</P>
<P>
Industry Minister John Manley and Environment Minister
Christine Stewart admitted that the government didn't have enough
scientific evidence to support its ban on the importation and
inter-provincial trade of the additive.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government said it will pay 13 million U.S.
dollars to Ethyl Corp. of the United States to compensate the MMT
manufacturer for loss of profit and costs because of the ban.
</P>
<P>
Ethyl Corp. has agreed to withdraw a 250-million-U.S.-dollar
suit against the Canadian government, which imposed the ban 13
months ago because of health and environment concerns.
</P>
<P>
MMT, methylcyclopentadienyl manganese tricarbonyl, is a
gasoline octane enhancer. Some studies have linked it to nervous
disorders.
</P>
<P>
The additive was banned in the U.S. briefly until a court
found last year that there was no basis for an Environment
Protection Agency ban. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Think-Tanks Predict Slower Italian Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Italian economic growth is expected
to be lower than the government's forecast of 2.5 percent for
1998, according to the two leading think-tanks -- the Institute
for Social Research (IRS) and the European Research Center (CER)
Monday.
</P>
<P>
But the institutions said other economic fundamentals may be
better than the government's forecast in its economic guidelines
for 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
The IRS said growth would be 1.9 percent, lower than the two
percent it predicted in April, while CER saw a growth of 2.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
While both saw the government as over-optimistic on growth, the
CER was even more up-beat on the ratio of public debt to gross
domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
It expected the ratio to drop as low as 106 percent by the end
of 2001, faster than Treasury Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi's debt
reentry plan.
</P>
<P>
The IRS said it was lowering its April estimates because of the
effects of the Asian financial crisis, especially a lower growth
in trade world-wide. It said the Asian crisis should taper off in
the next few months, though its effects would continue to be felt
in Italy for all of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Both of them forecast inflation this year at 1.8 percent, an
improvement for the IRS on its April forecast of two percent. For
1999, the IRS saw growth rising to 2.1 percent (2.4 percent
predicted in April) with inflation at 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is only in the year 2000 that the IRS believed Italy will
reach the 2.5 percent growth rate predicted by the government.
</P>
<P>
Despite its relative optimism, the CER expected no significant
drop in unemployment. The budget should remain under control and
the inflation rate stable, but always under two percent for the
three years in question, said the center.
</P>
<P>
According to the CER, short-term interest rates from 1998-2001
should remain below three percent in real terms. This is about 1.5
percent lower than in 1997, and about half the average for the
last decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mercosur's Small, Medium Companies to Increase Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The Southern Common Market
(Mercosur) member countries were trying to promote the small and
medium enterprises to increase their exports.
</P>
<P>
Officials from Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay, Paraguay and Bolivia
gathered here Monday at a seminar on small and medium enterprises
in the Mercosur.
</P>
<P>
Argentine President Carlos Menem said at the opening ceremony
that since the Mercosur was established in 1991, the regional
trade had risen from 3 billion U.S. dollars in 1991 to 20 billion
dollars, becoming the fourth biggest regional economic group in
which the small and medium companies made great contributions.
</P>
<P>
Menem also promised more support for the businesses in his
country.
</P>
<P>
Ana Kessler, activist of the Argentine small and medium
enterprises, said there are 900,000 small and medium enterprises
in Argentina which make up 50 percent of the gross domestic
product and provide 60 percent of employment.
</P>
<P>
Joaquin Fonseca Junior, president of the Brazilian Trade
Associations Confederation, said 92 percent of the companies in
Brazil are small and medium ones and provide 70 percent of the
jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, July 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The Southern Common Market (Mercosur) member
countries were trying to promote the small and medium enterprises
to increase their exports.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony of a seminar on small and medium
enterprises in the Mercosur on Monday, Argentine President Carlos
Menem said at the opening ceremony that since the Mercosur was
established in 1991, the regional trade had risen from three
billion U.S. dollars in 1991 to 20 billion dollars, becoming the
fourth biggest regional economic group in which the small and
medium companies made great contributions. (Mercosur-Export)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian economic growth is expected to be lower than
the government's forecast of 2.5 percent for 1998, according to
the two leading think-tanks -- the Institute for Social Research
(IRS) and the European Research Center (CER) Monday.
</P>
<P>
The IRS said growth would be 1.9 percent, lower than the two
percent it predicted in April, while CER saw a growth of 2.2
percent. But the institutions said other economic fundamentals may
be better than the government's forecast in its economic
guidelines for 1999-2000. (Italy-Economic Growth)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Car sales in Indonesia plunged by 82.4 percent in
the first half of this year, the Jakarta Post Tuesday quoted
industry statistics as saying.
</P>
<P>
The statistics, provided by the country's largest carmaker PT
Astra International, showed that car sales for the first half of
the year plunged to 35,789 units, sharply lower than the 203,212
units sold during the same period last year. Astra and the
country's other largest carmaker PT Indomobil Sukses Makmur have
halted production due to the slump in domestic demand, the report
said. (Indonesia-Car Sale)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- Kenyan tea prices increased at the weekly export
auction in the Indian Ocean port of Mombasa Monday, according to a
report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The rise was due to a strong demand from Pakistan and recent
cool weather which appears to slow tea growth, improve quality and
reduce quantities on offer, tea brokers were quoted as saying.
(Kenya-Tea) 
</P>
</TEXT>
