<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Russia Rakes up Five Golds Each in Athletics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Russia
continued their dominance in the athletics competition on the
second day of the 1998 Goodwill Games here today, each sweeping
five gold medals.
</P>
<P>
Kenya snatched two titles and Cuba won the rest one at the
Nassau County's Mitchel athletics complex in Long Island.
</P>
<P>
Four meet records fell in the final-only format competition,
and China's world record holder Jiang Bo put up a disastrous
performance in the women's 5,000 meters by wrapping up last.
</P>
<P>
Marion Jones of the United States swept a sprint double with a
win in the women's 200 meters in a meet record-breaking time of
21.80 seconds, beating the previous record of 22.09. The world
fastest woman won the 100 meters yesterday, also beating the meet
record.
</P>
<P>
U.S. world record holder Dan O'Brien collected a total of 8,755
points to win the men's decathlon, narrowly missing the world
record but good enough to beat the previous meet mark of 8,715.
</P>
<P>
Mark Crear gave the local crowd something to cheer when he
clocked 13.06 seconds in the men's 110-meter hurdles, knocking off
the meet record of 13.25 and beating world champion Allen Johnson
of the United States into second place. Briton world record
holder Colin Jackson wound up fourth.
</P>
<P>
Tisha Waller of the United States jumped over 1.97 meters to
win the women's high jump gold, and Angela Vaughn rounded up the
fifth title for the host by claiming the women's 100-meter hurdles
in 12.72 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Cuba's world champion Ivan Pedroso long jumped 8.54 meters to
underline his superiority in the event, beating Erick Walder of
the United States and James Beckford of Jamaica, who landed at
8.38 and 8.34.
</P>
<P>
"It was a good competition, the field was very strong," Pedroso
said after his triumph.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's world record holder Bernard Barmasai set a new meet
record in the men's 3,000-meter steeplechase with a time of
8:14.26, 0.04 seconds inside the old mark. Three-time world
champion Moses Kiptanui didn't finish the race.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Ndururi won another gold for Kenya by returning home
first in the men's 800 meters in 1:45.30, 0.20 seconds slower than
the meet record.
</P>
<P>
Russia's Olga Yegorova chalked up the women's 5,000 meters
title in a slow time of 15:53.05, followed by Libbie Hickman of
the United States and Lyubov Kremlyova of Russia.
</P>
<P>
China's Ma's Army runners Jiang Bo and Dong Yanmei, world
record beating runners last year in Shanghai, disappointed the
crowd here when they finished eighth and fourth respectively.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who set the world record 14:28.09 last October, followed
the two leading Russians in the third position most of the time,
with Dong, world number two last year, setting fourth.
</P>
<P>
Dong, who couldn't match up Yegorova's tremendous final kick,
cruised home in 16:00.56, more than one minute and half slower
than her personal best. Jiang, who never surged to the lead and
faded away from the first group with 400 meters to go.
</P>
<P>
Natalya Sadova tossed the plate to 65.80 meters to win the
women's discus, beating Olympic champion Ilke Wyludda of Germany
into second position.
</P>
<P>
Svetlana Masterkova and Ilya Markov won the other two golds for
Russia from the women's mile and men's 20km walk.
</P>
<P>
Tomorrow will produce 10 gold medals in the athletics
competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves 11.2 Billion Dollar Financing for Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) Monday announced the approval of a financial support
totaling 11.2 billion U.S. dollars for Russia.
</P>
<P>
The financing consists of an augmentation of Russia's extended
arrangement by the equivalent of about 8.3 billion dollars to
support the government's economic program for 1998, and about 2.9
billion dollars under the Compensatory and Contingency Financing
Facility (CCFF) to compensate for a shortfall in export earnings.
</P>
<P>
Of the augmented amount to be provided under the extended
arrangement, an equivalent of about 5.3 billion dollars is to be
made available under the Supplemental Reserve Facility (SRF).
</P>
<P>
The equivalent of some 4.8 billion dollars is available
immediately, comprising drawings of about 1 billion dollars under
the Extended Fund Facility (EFF), about 0.9 billion dollars under
the SRF and 2.9 billion dollars under the CCFF.
</P>
<P>
Russia's extended arrangement, for the equivalent of about 9.2
billion dollars, was approved in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
Russia joined the IMF in June 1992. Its quota is about 5.7
billion dollars and its outstanding use of IMF financing currently
totals about 14.3 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
