<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Volcano Refugees Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Around 7,000 refugees have
returned to their villages on the slopes of Merapi volcano in
Central Java, Indonesia, following a decrease in volcanic activity
in the area, reports reaching here Tuesday said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the decrease, the mountain, which had been spewing out
hot clouds since its eruption on July 11, was still gushing thick
clouds on Monday, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
As many as 5,000 people who fled the sub-district of Dukun,
Magelang regency, returned home early Monday, Sudjarwo, an
official in Dukun was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the villagers had insisted on returning home after
Mount Merapi appeared to have calmed down.
</P>
<P>
Around 2,000 villagers who fled from Serumbung sub-district in
the regency have also abandoned their temporary shelters and
returned home.
</P>
<P>
More than 40,000 people living in over ten villages on the
western slopes of he volcano fled to safer areas in Magelang as
volcanic areas in the mountain reached a critical level on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The 2,968-meter high volcano spewed out poisonous gases and
molten lava oozed out of the vent and ran down the Lamat,
Blongkeng, Boyong, sat, Seno and Jurong Jero lava canals. Hot
clouds shot out of the crater to an estimated height of 4,500
meters and ash covered the mountainside.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of hectares of paddy and tobacco plants in the Dukun
and Srumbung sub-districts were badly damaged by the ash, which
has been raining down incessantly since Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Merapi is one the most active volcanoes in the country. Three
major eruptions have been recorded in the past, the most of which
occurred in 1930 when 1,300 people were killed. The other two
eruptions were in 1994 and 1997, when a total of 88 people died.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
