<HEADLINE> Spain Backs Firms to Invest in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BILBAO, Spain, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Josep Pique Caps, minister
of industry and energy of Spain, said here Monday his government
will give financial backing to Spanish firms planing to invest in
China.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a trade and investment symposium, Pique said his
government has already provided such assistance to firms to help
their access to China in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Spain and China signed a financial agreement in May last year,
earmarking a credit of 600 million U.S. dollars to encourage
export to China.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish government also allocated five million dollars for
the feasibility studies of Spain-China cooperative projects.
</P>
<P>
The minister said Spain may provide more funds because "these
are not enough."
</P>
<P>
As China's political and economic influence are increasing, he
said, Spain needs a comprehensive and enduring action plan in its
economic and trade cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
The minister added, though suffering from the impact of Asian
financial turmoil, China's investment market is still growing.
</P>
