<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Opposes Nuclear Tests: Chuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Thailand opposes any nuclear
testing as well as stockpiling of nuclear arms by any country and
is therefore deeply concerned with the recent nuclear testings in
South Asia, Thailand's Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai told his
Pakistani counterpart Nawaz Sharif in a letter.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, dated July 17 and released by Thai Foreign
Ministry late Monday night, Chuan said that Thailand, a signatory
to the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty and the Comprehensive Test
Ban Treaty, is of the view that nuclear testings conducted by
India and Pakistan in May "heighten tensions, accelerate nuclear
arms race and create instability in South Asia."
</P>
<P>
"The actions also run contrary to the spirit of the
international community in promoting global nuclear
non-proliferation and disarmament," Chuan said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai prime minister also reiterated Thailand's stance on
supporting the establishment of nuclear free zones. He said the
nuclear testings in the South Asia region "run counter to" the
ASEAN's effort to establish a Zone of Peace, Freedom and
Neutrality and the Southeast Asia Nuclear Weapon Free Zone.
</P>
<P>
As a response to Sharif's earlier letter on nuclear tests
conducted by India and the instability in South Asia, the letter
also urged India and Pakistan to make joint endeavor to improve
relations between them and find a mutually acceptable solution to
the Kashmir problem.
</P>
<P>
"For peace and stability to prevail in South Asia, I urge that
countries in the region exercise utmost self-restraint and promote
confidence-building mechanisms to lead to solutions to the
existing regional conflicts," the Thai prime minister said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
