<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Claims More Lives in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The temperature in Dallas,
Texas hit 100 degrees Fahrenheit (38 C) for the 15th straight day
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The heat has claimed 81 lives in Texas, including 43 illegal
immigrants who had crossed the border from Mexico, according to
media reports.
</P>
<P>
The heat led to at least 22 deaths in Louisiana, 11 in Oklahoma
and one each in California, Arizona and Missouri. Temperatures hit
102 F (39 C) in parts of Oklahoma on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In Dallas, deputies headed into remote neighborhoods with
bottled water and electric fans on Monday to prevent more
fatalities.
</P>
<P>
"It's time for someone to literally go door to door to check on
the safety and welfare of the citizens we serve," The Associated
Press quoted Dallas County Sheriff Jim Bowles as saying.
</P>
<P>
Most people visited by Dallas County deputies were in
unincorporated areas of the county outside city or town limits.
Some live in mobile homes with no water or sewage systems.
</P>
<P>
"In many cases, these are almost forgotten enclaves of
disadvantaged citizens," Bowles said. "Many are elderly. Some
don't even have telephones to call for assistance."
</P>
<P>
Bowles estimated that 10,000 people live in the unincorporated
areas.
</P>
<P>
In Iowa, temperatures were in the 90s by early afternoon and
expected to climb as high as 105 F (40 C) in some spots.
</P>
<P>
In Oklahoma, fans and mist-spraying devices ran full blast at
poultry houses in the eastern part of the state to keep birds
cool. Chickens have died by the thousands in the past few weeks,
according to some unconfirmed reports.
</P>
<P>
In Nebraska, where temperatures crept toward 100, road work was
at a standstill as it was too hot to pour concrete.
</P>
<P>
The humid Northeast was expected to be the next hard-hit
region, with temperatures predicted to hit the 90s on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0263 </DOCNO>
