<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Not to Deploy Troops in Macedonia in near future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 20 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana said "NATO has no plans to deploy troops in Macedonia, let
alone adopt any form of military intervention" in clashes in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"Now we think the best way is to keep the U.N. Preventive
Deployment Forces (UNPREDF) in Macedonia longer," Solana told the
Macedonian daily New Macedonia, which carried the report on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Solana is expected to visit this country on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Considering the dangerous situation in Kosovo, Macedonia
expects NATO to deploy troops in the country to prevent
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
Solana indicated that even if NATO decides to deploy troops in
Macedonia in the end, the UNPREDF, whose term ends on August 31,
should stay.
</P>
<P>
Solana also said it is up to the international community, not
NATO, to decide Kosovo's future.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, NATO must be prepared for several alternative
actions. For the time being, NATO plans to hold multi-national
military exercises on the Krivolak base in central Macedonia in
September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
