<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Members Strongly Opposed to "Flexible Engagement" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- All the members of the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) but Thailand and the
Philippines are opposed to a proposed policy change from
"non-intervention" to "flexible engagement" in other members'
internal affairs, a senior official told Xinhua here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The official of an ASEAN member, who asked not to be named,
said that at an informal meeting of ASEAN senior officials Monday
night, all the other seven ASEAN members are "strongly opposed" to
the "flexible engagement" proposal, a departure from ASEAN's
traditional policy of non-intervention.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was made by Thai Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan
in a letter sent to Philippine Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon
last week. The proposal was backed by the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Siazon said earlier that since domestic developments in any
ASEAN member countries would have positive or adverse effects on
other members, he and the Thai foreign minister have called for "a
change in ASEAN's policy from constructive engagement to flexible
engagement, suggesting a more pro-active policy in the affairs of
other ASEAN countries."
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam and the
Philippines is the chairman of this year's ASEAN ministerial
meetings.
</P>
<P>
"If 'flexible engagement' only means giving advice to other
members, we have already been doing that. Why should we change our
traditional 'non-intervention' policy ?" the official asked.
</P>
<P>
A senior official from Indonesia also said that
"non-intervention" is the cardinal principle of ASEAN while
"flexible engagement," if adopted, would be against the U.N.
charter and the policy of the Non-aligned Movement.
</P>
<P>
"Why should we have a new policy?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a meeting of the ASEAN Standing Committee (ASC) and
a Senior Officials Meeting (SOM) opened here Tuesday to prepare
for the 31st ASEAN Ministerial Meeting scheduled for Friday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the ASC will focus on a review of the work of
ASEAN committees in implementing policies set by the AMM and
covering areas such as science and technology, the environment,
culture and information, social development, drugs and narcotics
control and civil service.
</P>
<P>
The ASC, the ASEAN's policy arm and organ of coordination of
ASEAN between ASEAN Ministerial Meetings (AMM), comprises the
chairman, who is the foreign minister of the country hosting the
annual AMM, the ASEAN secretary-general and the directors-general
of the ASEAN national secretariats.
</P>
<P>
The SOM meeting, formally institutionalized during the 1987
Manila summit, is responsible for ASEAN political cooperation and
is attended by senior officials and undersecretaries of member
countries.
</P>
<P>
It is to discuss on-going and possible areas of cooperation
between ASEAN member countries in the political arena including
confidence-building measures and the promotion of security and
stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
Both meetings are scheduled to close on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This year's ASEAN ministerial meeting is expected to discuss
topics including the financial turmoil in the region, ASEAN unity
and cooperation in face of the turmoil, Cambodia, nuclear
proliferation in South Asia and transnational crime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
