<HEADLINE> Qian: China Attaches Importance to Caribbean Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRIDGETOWN, Barbados, July 20 (Xinhua) -- China attaches great
importance to developing relations with Caribbean nations
including Barbados, said Chinese Vice Premier Qian Qichen here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed confidence that ties with the region will be
further strengthened through joint efforts.
</P>
<P>
Qian made the remarks at a meeting with Barbadian Governor-
General Cliford Husbands, who expressed his hope that Qian's visit
will help promote exchanges and cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Later on, Qian met Barbadian Prime Minister Owen Arthur at the
Prime Minister's Office, which is located at a picturesque beach
of the Caribbean Sea.
</P>
<P>
Arthur told Qian that Barbados pays great attention to ties
with China, noting that the relations have withstood the test of
time since they were established in 1977.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that the two sides have cooperated well on
international, regional and bilateral levels, Arthur expressed his
hope that Caribbean-China ties will also further be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
In reply, Qian said that China and Barbados, which are both
developing nations and share many common points, are close friends
who can be mutually trusted.
</P>
<P>
China believes that countries in the world should enjoy equal
status no matter how big, rich or strong they are, said Qian,
adding that China regards its relations with Barbados as an
important part of the South-South cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said that the aim of his visit is to enhance this
cooperation, which already exists between the two countries.
"Strengthening the exchanges and cooperation between the two
countries is in the interests of both peoples and conforms with
their wishes."
</P>
<P>
Qian also highly praised the one-China policy which has long
been upheld by the Barbadian government, and expressed his
gratitude to Barbados for its efforts in helping develop relations
between China and those countries which have no diplomatic ties
with China.
</P>
<P>
On economic and trade cooperation, Qian said good basis has
been laid and strengthening it is a common task of both sides.
</P>
<P>
China and Barbados enjoy a good political relationship and have
the desire to cooperate, said the vice premier. The Chinese
government supports more business between enterprises of the two
countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
Following their meeting, Qian and Arthur signed an agreement on
encouragement and protection of investment in both countries.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who arrived here on Saturday, met President Neville
Vernon Nicholls of the Caribbean Development Bank (CDB) on Sunday
afternoon. China became a full member of the bank in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
