<HEADLINE> Two Women's Tennis Opens in Indonesia Cancelled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The WTA Tour, the women's
professional tennis circuit government body, has dropped two open
tournaments in Indonesia from its calendar this year due to
security concerns, the Jakarta Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The tournament in Indonesia's second largest city of Surabaya
was scheduled for September 28 to October 4, and the Jakarta Open
was slated on November 9 to November 15.
</P>
<P>
WTA Operations manager Linda Christensen said in a July 17
faxed letter to the Indonesian Tennis Association that the
decision was made after an inspection of the cities.
</P>
<P>
"The Tour recently conducted security risk checks for the
cities of Surabaya and Jakarta. Given the strong chance that
Indonesia will become more volatile and the possibility for
further violent unrest in Surabaya and Jakarta later in the year,
it is not in the best interests of the Tour players or officials
to travel to these cities at this time," Christensen said.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, based on these results, both tournaments have been
cancelled for good," Christensen added.
</P>
<P>
In response to the WTA Tour's decision, deputy
secretary-general of the Indonesian Tennis Association Subiyanto
said: "It's too bad to cancel both tournaments just because of
security reasons."
</P>
<P>
Riots shook several Indonesian cities in the wake of student
movements that culminated in the ouster of former president
Soeharto in May.
</P>
<P>
Security worries have also been blamed for disrupting other
sports events in the country. The Indonesian Open badminton
championships has been moved back from August to November, while
the soccer league was prematurely halted in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
