<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ASEAN And Its Annual Meetings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN has been playing a more and
more important role in the Asia-Pacific region by hosting a number
of events to increase the cohesion of ASEAN nations and strengthen
ties with outside countries.
</P>
<P>
These events include the ASEAN Ministerial Meeting (AMM), the
ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF) and the ASEAN Post Ministerial
Conferences (PMC).
</P>
<P>
From July 21 to 29, the three annual meetings will take place
in the Philippines, ASEAN's rotating chairman this year.
</P>
<P>
AMM is responsible for the formulation of policy guidelines and
coordination of ASEAN activities while ARF serves as a
multilateral consultative forum aimed at promoting "preventive
diplomacy and confidence building" among the nations in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The forum is currently attended by the nine ASEAN member
countries, the 10 ASEAN dialogue partners (Australia, Canada,
China, the European Union, India, Japan, New Zealand, Russia,
South Korea and the United States) and the two observers Cambodia
and Papua New Guinea.
</P>
<P>
During the PMC, ASEAN countries will exchange views on
political and security issues with the dialogue partners. There
will be a plenary session and separate individual sessions between
ASEAN and each dialogue partner.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon, the chairman of
the meetings, said the ongoing Asian financial crisis and its
widespread social impacts, nuclear arms race in South Asia, the
forthcoming Cambodian elections, fight against transnational
crimes, concerns over Japan's economic and political woes and drug
and narcotics control are among the highlights of the meetings.
</P>
<P>
He said the Manila gatherings provide an incomparable
opportunity "to put focus on the current economic situation and
consider its implications on the countries within Asia, as well as
those beyond."
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the PMC, for the first time, will issue a
joint statement on the financial crisis which started last July
and has plagued Southeast and East Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
This year's AMM might be a turning point in ASEAN's history. In
response to the financial and economic crisis, Thailand and the
Philippines are "informally" calling for a change in ASEAN's
policy from "non-interference" to "flexible engagement."
</P>
<P>
"Flexible engagement" means that when domestic developments in
an ASEAN country have had positive or adverse effects on its
neighbors, other ASEAN nations can "flexibly intervene" in the
affairs of the said country, Siazon explained.
</P>
<P>
However, as some ASEAN members are not keen on such an idea, no
consensus seems likely to emerge from the meeting, analysts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic News Briefs From Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Following are economic news
briefs from Latin America.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- The Venezuelan government will emit new export bonds
of almost 24 million U.S. dollars in a bid to benefit the
agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
Daniela Romagni, vice-president of the Foreign Commerce Bank,
said the bonds will be negotiable, but will not generate
interests, because they will be basically used to pay taxes on
behalf of the beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- There are 1,100 credit unions in Brazil with a
million of associates and a total capital of 1.4 billion
U.S. dollars. They are able to lend money to members at a monthly
rate of two to five percent.
</P>
<P>
Dejandir Dalpasquale, president of the Credit Union
Organization, said that in 1989 there were only 300 credit unions
in the country.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The total expenditure of the Costa Rican government
reached 1.260 billion U.S. dollars in the first half of this year,
representing an increase of 16.7 percent compared to the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Of the fund, 25.76 percent goes to salaries of civil servants,
13.82 percent to pensions, 6.38 percent to college education, 2.9
percent to teachers salaries, according to the Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the government paid about 241.46 million
U.S. dollars in interests on foreign debts, accounting for 24.1
percent of the total expenditure of the public sector.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico produces every year about 15,000 tons of
certified seeds to meet 20 percent of the domestic need.
</P>
<P>
Artemio Iglesias Miramontes, director of the Seeds National
Manufacturer, said the seeds sold in the domestic market are corn,
jicamas, wheat, rice, sesame, alfalfa, habanero and serrano pepper.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The exports of Panama in the first half of this
year reached 274 million U.S. dollars, an increase of 23.7 percent
over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian Institute of Foreign Affairs said in a report
that manufactured goods and seafood generated more than other
export items, making 42 million and 30 million dollars each.
</P>
</TEXT>
