<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Association of Southeast Asian Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) was established on August 8, 1967, in Bangkok,
Thailand, with the signing of the Bangkok Declaration by the five
original member countries namely Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Declaration united the five member countries in a
joint effort to promote economic cooperation and the welfare of
the people in the region. It set out the guidelines for ASEAN's
activities and defined the aims of the organization.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN nations came together with three main objectives in
mind: to promote the economic, social and cultural development of
the region through cooperative programs; to safeguard the
political and economic stability of the region; and to serve as a
forum for the resolution of intra-regional differences.
</P>
<P>
During the first ASEAN summit meeting in Bali, Indonesia, in
1976, ASEAN set up a small secretariat in Jakarta, Indonesia, to
provide administrative support and help for the coordination of
ASEAN activities.
</P>
<P>
Brunei Darussalam joined ASEAN in January 1984, making the
regional political, security and economic organization a
six-member group until July 1995 when Vietnam was admitted to
ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
During the past three decades, ASEAN nations have cooperated on
a wide range of issues from politics, economy and security to
science and technology, environment, culture, social development,
drugs and narcotics control and civil service.
</P>
<P>
Political and security cooperation in ASEAN began in its
formative years. Some of the most important accords adopted by
ASEAN include the 1971 declaration designating Southeast Asia as a
Zone of Peace, Freedom and Neutrality, the Treaty of Amity and
Cooperation in Southeast Asia and the Declaration of ASEAN Concord
in 1976.
</P>
<P>
These accords stated ASEAN's intentions and commitment to
building regional resilience free from any form and any manner of
interference by outside powers, a code of international conduct
governing peaceful relations among countries in the region and the
principles and framework for ASEAN cooperation in the political,
security, economic and functional fields.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, ASEAN absorbed Vietnam as its seventh member country
at the ministerial meeting held in Brunei. At the end of the same
year, the Fifth ASEAN Summit in Thailand decided to develop ASEAN
into a 10-member group including Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion of ASEAN's 30th anniversary last year, Laos and
Myanmar joined ASEAN. However, ASEAN postponed Cambodia's
accession due to the newly-emerged political unrest in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Another most significant step taken by ASEAN is the proposed
establishment of the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) by the year
2008. In 1995, ASEAN's heads of government agreed to accelerate
the scheme by reducing the time frame from 15 years to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The primary objective of AFTA is to promote greater foreign
direct investments and intra-ASEAN investments in the region.
According to the ASEAN Common Effective Preferential Tariff Scheme
for AFTA, ASEAN must cut tariffs to no more than 5 percent by the
year 2003. So far, more than 90 percent of ASEAN's total tariff
lines have already been included in the scheme, thus making a
giant step toward free trade within the ASEAN region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
