<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Opens ASC, SOM Meetings in Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast Asian
Association (ASEAN) opened a meeting of the ASEAN Standing
Committee (ASC) and a Senior Officials Meeting (SOM) here Tuesday
to prepare for the 31st ASEAN Ministerial Meeting scheduled for
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon told reporters
Monday that the meeting of the ASC will focus on a review of the
work of ASEAN committees in implementing policies set by the AMM
and covering areas such as science and technology, the
environment, culture and information, social development, drugs
and narcotics control and civil service.
</P>
<P>
The ASC, the ASEAN's policy arm and organ of coordination of
ASEAN between ASEAN Ministerial Meetings (AMM), comprises the
chairman, who is the foreign minister of the country hosting the
annual AMM, the ASEAN secretary-general and the directors-general
of the ASEAN national secretariats.
</P>
<P>
The SOM meeting, formally institutionalized during the 1987
Manila summit, is responsible for ASEAN political cooperation and
is attended by senior officials and undersecretaries of member
countries.
</P>
<P>
It is to discuss on-going and possible areas of cooperation
between ASEAN member countries in the political arena including
confidence-building measures and the promotion of security and
stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam and the
Philippines is the chairman of this year's ASC and SOM.
</P>
<P>
Both meetings are scheduled to close on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, most foreign ministers and other officials of ASEAN
member countries arrived here Monday for the ministerial meeting,
which is expected to discuss topics including the financial
turmoil in the region, ASEAN unity and cooperation in face of the
turmoil, Cambodia, nuclear proliferation in South Asia and
transnational crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: ASEAN Facing Greater Challenges (1)  (By Chen Hegao, Liu Huorong) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) will start their
annual meeting here Friday to work out new strategies to meet a
series of political, social and economic challenges facing the
group.
</P>
<P>
Since the ministers met in Malaysia a year ago, drastic
political, social and economic changes have taken place in the
region of ASEAN, which groups Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, Brunei, Vietnam, Laos and
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Mainly due to a one-year-old regional financial crisis,
economic growth in most ASEAN members has slowed down to a pace
that is a far cry from what used to be the highest in the world;
political unrest has forced Thailand and Indonesia to change
guards; social stability in other Southeast Asian countries has
also been undermined by protests, strikes and riots; the recent
nuclear tests by India and Pakistan have raised tension in South
Asia and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
In Cambodia, where a general election is scheduled for Sunday,
a lasting peace needs more efforts by all the political parties in
the country and assistance from the international community,
including the ASEAN, which would accept Cambodia as a 10th member
in the future.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said, the continuation of the financial
crisis and the deterioration of the economic situation are posing
the most grave challenge to the ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
Over the past year, countries in the region have been severely
affected by the financial turmoil. Since Thailand floated its
currency, the baht, on July 2, 1997, a wave of currency
devaluations has spread over Southeast Asia, and the currencies of
Thailand, the Philippines, Malaysia, Indonesia and Singapore have
lost 15 percent to nearly 80 percent of their value.
</P>
<P>
The currency devaluations have led to high interest rates,
soaring inflation and an increase in U.S. dollar-denominated
foreign debts in Southeast Asia. The crisis has thrown millions of
Southeast Asians out of work as corporations are forced to close
or trim their payrolls, or downsize for the sake of survival.
</P>
<P>
In Indonesia alone, 13.4 million people have lost their jobs, a
five-fold increase from the pre-crisis level.
</P>
<P>
With the full-blown impact being felt this year, Indonesia and
Thailand have entered a period of economic recession during the
first half of the year. Malaysia also saw a negative 1.8-percent
growth in its gross domestic product in the first quarter, while
the Philippine economy increased by only 1.7 percent, much lower
than its target.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: ASEAN Facing Greater Challenges (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
What has made the economic situation turn from bad to worse is
the economic recession in Japan and a weak yen in particular. The
Japanese economy has registered negative growth in two consecutive
quarters, the first quarter of this year and the last quarter of
1997. The recession failed to lift the weak yen, which fell to 146
against the greenback in mid-June and around 140 since the U.S.
intervention on June 16.
</P>
<P>
The yen's weakness has rendered ASEAN products less attractive
to Japanese consumers, blocking ASEAN exports to Japan. In April,
Japan's imports from ASEAN countries declined by 26 percent
compared with that a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The slump in the Japanese economy would impede the economic
recovery of ASEAN countries from the current crisis as Japan is
Southeast Asia's major creditor, economists here noted.
</P>
<P>
Since ASEAN is facing the severe economic challenge, the ASEAN
Ministerial Meeting and its related meetings -- the 5th ASEAN
Regional Forum and the Post Ministerial Conference -- are an
incomparable opportunity to put focus on the financial crisis and
consider its implications for the countries within Asia and for
those beyond the region.
</P>
<P>
Under the region's deteriorating economic situation, forest
fires in Indonesia and other ASEAN countries over the past year
have caused huge economic losses and environmental problems in the
region. According to estimates by environmental watchdogs, forest
fire-related losses in 1997 amounted to more than 3 billion U.S.
dollars mainly in Indonesia and Malaysia, with an additional 1.4
billion dollars in economic losses for the region from the haze
generated by the fires.
</P>
<P>
Although most of the fires have been put out by rains so far in
these countries, renewed threat of fires and smogs emerged again
with fresh forest fires reported in Indonesia's Sumatra.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said ASEAN countries must find out ways to change the
slash-and-burn tradition to eliminate sources of forest fires,
which have eaten up thousands of hectares of forests in the region
in the past year.
</P>
<P>
As the founding fathers of ASEAN dreamed of an association
comprising all countries in Southeast Asia, nine countries in the
region have joined ASEAN, leaving out only Cambodia, which is now
the key to the realization of the dream. At last year's ASEAN
Ministerial Meeting, the political developments in Cambodia
prevented the group from accepting the country as a new member.
Since then, the ASEAN has made great efforts to promote peace in
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The country's general election next week could pave the way for
its membership, but ASEAN countries need to continue to express
concern and extend fraternal cooperation and assistance to ensure
a lasting peace in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, according to Philippine Foreign Secretary Domingo
Siazon, chairman of this year's ASEAN ministerial meeting, the
ASEAN is not turning a blind eye to the nuclear tests conducted by
India and Pakistan earlier this year and the ASEAN Ministerial
Meeting and its related meetings will pursue this issue.
</P>
<P>
Observers believe that so long as ASEAN members make joint
efforts and continue their cooperation, they can tackle all these
problems and make new contributions to peace and development in
the region and the rest of the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0296 </DOCNO>
