<HEADLINE> Philippines Plans to Lift Rice Import Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
planning to remove existing import restrictions on three sensitive
agricultural products -- sugar, rice and corn -- to help producers
cope with the rising cost of production.
</P>
<P>
The National Economic and Development Authority (NEDA), the
country's socio-economic planning agency, is studying the issue,
the newspaper Business World reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
NEDA Secretary General Felipe Medalla was quoted as saying
while the NEDA is aware of the prospective policy's impact on
farmers, the government faces a pressing concern to see to it that
the economic environment is not too restrictive for industries.
</P>
<P>
"Any protection on agricultural products is anti-industry ...
and anything that makes food expensive is a tax on food," he said.
</P>
<P>
Medalla said that in the Philippines, almost 50 percent of an
average worker's money is spent on food, indicating the importance
of removing the importation restrictions.
</P>
<P>
"What we are aiming for is to privatize the decision to
import," he said.
</P>
<P>
Medalla said the proposed policy is in line with the new
administration's action agenda which puts top priority on food
security.
</P>
<P>
Estrada has promised to guarantee food security by abolishing
the monopoly of the National Food Authority on food importation.
</P>
</TEXT>
