<HEADLINE> Argentina's Iron, Steel Production Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Argentina registered a big
increase in its production of iron and steel during the first half
of this year.
</P>
<P>
Iron output grew 13.4 percent during the said six months,
compared to the same period in 1997, and crude steel production
grew by 4.6 percent, according to the country's Iron and Steel
Center (CIS).
</P>
<P>
CIS said in a report on Monday that iron production reached
330,839 tons in June, 2.3 percent less than the 338,700 tons
produced in May, but 14.9 percent more than the 288,000 tons made
during the same month in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The production of crude steel in June was 371,036 tons, 4.3
percent more than the 356,500 tons produced in June of 1997.
</P>
<P>
CIS added that 125,063 tons of steel strips were produced in
June this year, 1.5 percent more than the 123,200 tons produced in
June 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
