<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Sees Lower Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' inflation rate,
which peaked at 10.7 percent in June 1998, will likely recede in
the rest of the year, the Philippine Journal reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Socio-economic Planning Secretary Felipe Medalla was quoted by
the newspaper as saying that the National Economic and Development
Authority (NEDA) expects the inflation rate to start going down
starting in July.
</P>
<P>
Medalla, who is also secretary general of NEDA, also predicted
that interest rates, determined each week by the benchmark 91-day
Treasury Bills, could still go down some more "but realistically
not to its pre-crisis level of less than 10 percent."
</P>
<P>
The benchmark rate went down on Monday by 56.3 basis points to
14.195 percent from 14.756 percent last week, according to the
Bureau of Treasury. The slowdown is expected to be reflected in
the lending rates of banks.
</P>
<P>
Medalla confirmed that inflation will average above 10 percent
under the new method using the base year 1994.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will put in place macroeconomic policies
consistent with relatively low inflation and interest rates to
achieve overall growth of 2 to 3 percent this year and domestic
growth of 1.5 percent up to 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Medalla said the recent uptrend in inflation could not be
attributed to wrong macroeconomic policies but to food supply
constraints and to increased uncertainty in the financial markets
in general. 
</P>
</TEXT>
