<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Say More Cows Are Needed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Some experts in Hangzhou, the
capital of east China's Zhejiang Province, say that more attention
needs to be paid to the dairy industry in China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese eat a lot of pork and less milk, and replacing pigs
with cows could give Chinese healthier bodies, while reducing the
amount of grain consumption, these members of the China Rice
Institute and the Zhejiang Provincial Academy of Agricultural
Sciences say.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese are mainly engaged in grain production and raising
pigs and are not so used to foods like milk and cheese and Chinese
milk output is only about 1 percent of the world's total, but its
population accounts for a fifth of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the average per-capita daily intake of protein for
Chinese was 64.2 g., 20 percent of that from animal products. The
world's average was 70.9 g.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, if the average amount of protein intake for Chinese
reaches the world's level of 1996, the country will need to
produce 6.27 million tons more animal protein, which means it
needs 16 million tons of fodder if cows are used, or 49 million
tons, if pigs are used, researchers say.
</P>
<P>
Cows produce the same amount of animal protein but use 65
percent less feed, they say and point out that pigs are fed with
grain, and that 540 million tons of grain, which is the output of
36 million ha. of farmland, are needed to produce 49 million tons
of fodder and this does not fit China's reality.
</P>
<P>
In addition, cows mainly feed on grass and straw, which
requires a much smaller growing area than that needed for pigs,
according to the experts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
