<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maintaining Air Quality In Southern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING July 21 (Xinhua) -- Beihai, a port city in southwest
China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, has maintained good air
quality for several years now.
</P>
<P>
Its pollution index has ranged from 30 to 40, far lower than
the 50 for Category I air quality, based on the amount of sulphur
dioxide, nitrogen and oxide compounds, and suspended particles.
</P>
<P>
No serious polluters are allowed in the city, and attention is
paid to preventing industrial pollution, according to Ke Jinhua,
director of the Beihai City Pollution Control Office.
</P>
<P>
The city has 6 sq.m. of green space per capita and its 3 steel
plants all using gas and electricity as fuel instead of coal, he
said.
</P>
<P>
One air-quality monitor indicated an index of 52 in March,
which aroused great concern among government departments. An
investigation was conducted to track the pollution source and
steps were taken to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
Beihai is a 28-sq.km. area with 180,000 people on the southern
tip of the autonomous region, and has the sea on three sides and
sea breezes can have a cleansing effect, Ke explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
