<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Seeks Changes in ICC Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Monday that it would oppose ratification and implementation of a
treaty of setting up an International Criminal Court (ICC) if
its demand for changes to the treaty should be turned down.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters the
United States was at odds with the treaty in its present form
because it could adopt frivolous or politically motivated
war-crime prosecutions against U.S. military personnel
conducting operations abroad.
</P>
<P>
"It could inhibit the ability of the United States to meet
alliance obligations and participate in international
peacekeeping operations," he said at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
The treaty of setting up the International Criminal Court was
approved in Rome By 120 countries last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the court would be deluged with complaints from
well-meaning individuals and organizations that would want the
court to redress every wrong in the world. "This will turn the
court into a human rights ombudsman and limit its ability to
investigate the most serious crimes," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is hard to see how the United States can support such a
court ... We are going to try to convince the people who were so
determined to create this in a rushed way to think hard, think
again, try to correct the mistakes and put us in a position to
try to join the regime," he added.
</P>
<P>
"If not, if then we believe that our national interest could
be affected, we intend to reserve the right to actively oppose
it. It needs some repair work, desperately," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said unless the ICC treaty is changed, Washington would
not accept the jurisdiction of a court set up in what he called
"such a flawed and mistaken way."
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to pursue what we think we need to do
around the world, including deploying forces as appropriate," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
