<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Fails in Agreement with Panama on Drug Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Monday
expressed pessimism over negotiations with Panama to establish
an international drug interdiction center in the country.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin acknowledged the impasse
that the negotiations are now in, saying "the prospects are not
good."
</P>
<P>
During two years of the negotiations, the United States
insisted that the U.S. military be allowed to carry out
unilateral activities such as search and rescue operations,
training flights, humanitarian relief and logistical support
beyond Panama's borders after Washington hands over the
authority of the Panama Canal in 1999.
</P>
<P>
But Panama has objected to the U.S. suggestions and the
negotiations have so far been in stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Failure to reach an agreement would mean the United States
must withdraw its military forces from Panama by the end of
1999, when the Panama Canal reverts to local control under terms
of the Panama Canal treaties. It would mean an end to
Panama-based operations by the U.S. military aimed at curbing
flows of U.S.-bound cocaine from South America.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said that in the light of the impasse, the United
States has decided to begin pursuit of alternative
anti-narcotics arrangements with other governments.
</P>
<P>
"This doesn't mean that these negotiations won't ever yield
success, but it means the prospects are not good and therefore
we need to be able to be making alternative arrangements," he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
