<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Starr Speeds up White House Scandal Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr, who is investigating the White House scandal, brought the
grand jury in for an extra day this week to hear testimony by U.S.
President Bill Clinton's bodyguards and major witness Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
The closed-door panel that has been hearing evidence since
January in the case of alleged illicit sex and cover-up is
expected to meet Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday, adding a session
to its usual schedule of Tuesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Starr summoned seven current and former Secret
Service personnel to the federal courthouse in Washington, minutes
after Supreme Court Chief Justice William Rehnquist rejected a
Justice Department appeal.
</P>
<P>
Starr's staff is reportedly putting in long hours during the
week and on weekends at the counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
However, Starr's spokesman Charles Bakaly discouraged reports
of any timetable for finishing the inquiry or delivering a final
report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court decision to let Secret Service employees
testify was a setback for the Clinton administration, which had
argued in court that the president's bodyguards should have a
so-called protective function privilege, which would shield them
against being compelled to testify about what they witness while
on duty.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the Secret Service, Tripp is expected to return
for more testimony before the grand jury. After six full days of
testimony, Tripp, her lawyers had said, still has more to say to
the panel.
</P>
<P>
Tripp taped some 20 hours of telephone talk with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky, which reportedly involves discussion
of a presidential affair.
</P>
<P>
Both Lewinsky and Clinton have denied the affair in sworn
statements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Furor Over Secrecy of Mandela's Wedding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Doubtful secrecy over South
African President Nelson Mandela's marriage to Graca Machel on
Saturday frustrated local and international media, which
questioned the credibility of the president's office Monday.
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesman Parks Mankahlana had categorically
denied that the wedding was to take place.
</P>
<P>
The Star newspaper wrote on Monday that for three days it
insisted it was true that Mandela and Machel were getting
married, and for three days the president's office denied it. But
The Star was right.
</P>
<P>
As late as Friday afternoon, Mandela's office made an appeal
to the media to discontinue the "false rumors" that the president
was to get married on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The rumors are false and we would like the president and his
family to enjoy the tranquillity they deserve on his 80th
birthday," Mankahlana said.
</P>
<P>
Cape Town's Afrikaans daily, Die Burger, in an editorial
Monday called for Mankahlana's dismissal because his credibility
as the presidential spokesman had collapsed, according to South
African Press Association (SAPA).
</P>
<P>
The South African National Editors Forum (SANEF) said although
the wedding was a private affair, it was badly handled by
Mandela's office.
</P>
<P>
"We acknowledge that this is private affair... but from the
presidential spokesman's point of view, I believe there were
better ways of handling it than it has been," said SANEF
chairman, Mike Siluma.
</P>
<P>
It was important that the presidential aide be trusted, even
on a not important function like a wedding, he said.
</P>
<P>
Brendon Boyle, head of Reuters' southern African bureau, also
said the matter was mishandled.
</P>
<P>
"For the president's office to deliberately mislead the media
once the news of the wedding had been leaked, sets a very
dangerous precedent for the future," Boyle said.
</P>
<P>
Other reports said Monday that only two to three photographers
and one TV crew were invited and were apparently selling the
pictures and footage at exorbitant prices.
</P>
<P>
One photographer was reportedly selling the Mandela/Machel
wedding pictures at a price of 1,000 U.S. Dollars per photo.
</P>
<P>
The big question raised on Monday by various media
organizations was who was the beneficiary of the proceeds from
the wedding footage and photo sales as there had been no clarity
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The suspicion was that people were taking advantage of
Mandela's international stature to enrich themselves.
</P>
<P>
The Star said the veil of secrecy thrown over the wedding was
at least partly to protect the interests of a publishing company
which had bought the rights to the story for an undisclosed
amount of money.
</P>
<P>
It said Mafube intended to produce a special publication on
the wedding in two weeks' time.
</P>
<P>
But Mafube denied the allegations, saying it paid nothing to
be at Mandela's wedding.
</P>
<P>
In a statement on Monday evening, Mandela's office admitted
that it might have overstepped the mark in its attempt to uphold
Mandela's privacy in his marriage.
</P>
<P>
"It is possible that the office of the president and its
officials overstepped the mark in its attempt to uphold the
president's privacy," the office said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
But it argued that this was a matter of conjecture about which
there would always be argumentation.
</P>
<P>
"We would urge our detractors not to conflate government
policy with the private wishes of the presidential couple," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said officials of the president's office understood the
considerable frustration of the media in not being able to
publish and have access to the wedding.
</P>
<P>
"The president's marriage was, and still is, a very popular
story which every news organization or newspaper would like to
report on. It at the same time remained a private matter," the
statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Leader Announces New Economic Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar Monday night announced a new package of
economic policies, including the cancellation of the dual
exchange system, improved infrastructure and others.
</P>
<P>
In a nationally televised broadcast, Abubakar announced the
cancellation of the dual exchange system, one being the fixed 22
Naira to one U.S. Dollar and the other market-determined rate of
about 85 Naira to one Dollar.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar also promised to improve the country's
infrastructure, including better power and fuel supply, improved
telecommunications and transportation services.
</P>
<P>
To this end, he said the government will give up its minimum
of 40 percent ownership in major state-owned firms such as the
National Electrical Power Authority and the Nigerian
Telecommunications, among others.
</P>
<P>
The proceeds from the process, he said, will be used to pay
the country's foreign debt, which stood at 27 billion U.S.
Dollars as at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar promised to invest more on the oil industry, which
provides more than 70 percent of the government's revenue and 90
percent of the country's foreign currency income.
</P>
<P>
He has ordered the immediate negotiation of a medium term
economic plan with the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria will also start discussions with the Paris Club on
debt relief, he said, adding that his government will liberalize
the current debt conversion program to attract more foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar promised to review the salary system for civil
servants annually, for which he ordered the suspension of the
rationalization practice initiated by former head of state late
General Sani Abacha last year.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that as a means to combat rampant
corruption, all contracts for constructions and supply of
equipment, goods and services will hereafter be subject to
competitive bidding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
