<HEADLINE> Nigeria Sets New Date for Military Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar Monday night unveiled a much-awaited new date
for the end of the military rule in the country.
</P>
<P>
In a broadcast to the nation which was just concluded, General
Abubakar said the presidential elections will be completed at the
end of the first quarter 1999 and the president elect will be
inaugurated on May 29 that year.
</P>
<P>
The announcement gave an eight-month delay to the military
government's transition to civil rule program set by former head
of state late General Sani Abacha, who died of heart attack on
June 8.
</P>
<P>
Under Abacha's program, presidential elections would be held
from August 1 this year and the president elect be sworn in on
October 1.
</P>
<P>
The major policy change is a result of the wide consultations
between Abubakar's government and various interest groups across
the country since Abubakar became the head of state the second
day after the sudden death of Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The soft-spoken general also announced the dissolution of the
five registered political parties and the National Electoral
Commission of Nigeria with immediate effect, to be replaced by a
truly independent new one.
</P>
<P>
Both the parties and the commission were set up during
Abacha's time.
</P>
<P>
The results of state and national assembly elections already
conducted have also been cancelled for new arrangements, because
of their lack of credibility and acceptability, Abubakar said.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to widespread speculations, Abubakar, 56, ruled out
the establishment of a government of national unity as demanded
by some groups.
</P>
<P>
He said such a government poses dangers that are unacceptable
to his administration.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar, however, promised to form a new cabinet that will
accommodate various interest groups.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet formed by Abacha in mid-December last year was
dissolved under the order of Abubakar about two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
He also announced the release of all political detainees as a
means to further promote national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
About 40 political detainees have been freed since Abubakar
assumed office. Ten of them were released earlier Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Granting Interest Credits for Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian government Monday
announced a package of measures, including a wheat fund, to
protect domestic farmers.
</P>
<P>
Romania is expected to record this year a good wheat crop, but
the farmers are worrying about the market, as the world's wheat
price is the lowest in the last 17 years. Since customs duties for
wheat and flour are quite low, there is the risk that Romanian
market will be invaded by imported wheat and flour.
</P>
<P>
According to Minister of Agriculture Dinu Gavrilescu, the
government wanted to set up a wheat fund worth 1,000 billion lei
(115 million U.S. dollars) for granting credits with 50 percent
subsidized interest to the wheat storage units and those of
milling and bakery that buy Romanian wheat.
</P>
<P>
The Government agreed at the same time to allocate 200 billion
lei (23 million U.S. dollars) from the budget to purchase and
store wheat from Romanian producers.
</P>
<P>
The customs duties on imported wheat and flour are also to be
increased from a present 15-25 percent to 60 percent to protect
domestic producers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0331 </DOCNO>
