<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Shilling Strongest vs U.S. Dollar Since </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan Shilling Monday
reached its strongest exchange rate against the U.S. Dollar since
last August when a multi-million-Dollar aid package was suspended
by the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Some local traders said they were expecting the Shilling to
strengthen further in the near future while analysts warned the
currency is already overvalued and may not be able to sustain
these levels indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) posted the Shilling at a
commercial mean-opening rate of 59.3878 to the Dollar, its
strongest opening rate since August 1, 1997, according to CBK
data.
</P>
<P>
At 12:00 a.m. local time (0900 GMT), the Shilling was at
around 59.30/45 to the Dollar, said the dealers.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the Shilling's direction was mainly driven by
trade flows, with speculative activity relatively low. Meanwhile,
they put as the next target 59.00 Shillings to the Dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Shilling fell drastically last August to around 70 to the
Dollar after the IMF cut the key loan citing corruption and poor
governance in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
The Shilling's previous strongest opening for 1998 was
59.4006, set on July 3, CBK data shows. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Govt Unveils Plans to Reform Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Labor government on
Monday unveiled a massive program to boost public transport and
end the nightmare of congestion on Britain's roads.
</P>
<P>
In his long-awaited transport White Paper, Deputy Prime
Minister and Transport Secretary John Prescott promised investment
to encourage the use of buses and trains and to persuade people to
abandon their cars.
</P>
<P>
Brushing aside accusations that he was squeezing the car-lovers
of Middle England, Prescott told parliament: "The most anti-car
policy is to do nothing. Pro-public transport does not mean being
anti-car."
</P>
<P>
Prescott predicted that without action now, traffic on
Britain's already crowded roads would grow by 30 percent in the
next 20 years. Carbon dioxide emissions would increase 10 percent
at a time when Britain is required under last year's Kyoto accord
on global warming to cut emissions of so-called greenhouse gases.
</P>
<P>
He said local councils will be given powers to charge car
drivers for using congested roads and for workplace parking. The
cash raised will be ring-fenced for spending on the public
transport system, a new departure in Britain where revenue has
traditionally gone straight to the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
The government's Highways Agency will be given new powers to
pilot road charging schemes and use the income to reinvest in the
road network.
</P>
<P>
Under the new plan, there will be new moves to provide safe
routes for children to walk or cycle to school to end the
congestion caused by parents driving them there at peak hours.
</P>
<P>
Pensioners will also be given a national concessionary fare
scheme, guaranteeing them at least half-price bus fares.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prescott spelt out a range of measures to improve
the privatized rail network, while ruling out any return to public
ownership.
</P>
<P>
According to him, an extra 100 million pounds will be invested
to the rail industry and a new strategic rail authority will be
set up, which will police Britain's privatized rail network and
provide tougher regulation of rail companies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980721.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Japan to Speak Less, Do More on Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 20 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Monday
urged Japan to speak less and do more for recovery from
recession.
</P>
<P>
"Japan needs to speak less and carry a big stick," Assistant
U.S. Treasury Secretary Timothy Geithner said. "They need to
demonstrate by what they do, not by what they say they might do,
to turn this thing around."
</P>
<P>
Gaithner made the remarks as three candidates are fighting
to take over Japan's premiership after Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto resigned a week ago on losing support in an Upper
House of Parliament election.
</P>
<P>
All of them have promised to try and wrench the world's second
biggest economy from a deep and painful recession. And Japanese
people are awaiting the outcome of the three-horse race.
</P>
<P>
Geithner reiterated U.S. demands for Japan to take urgent
steps to stimulate domestic demand, clean up the ailing
financial sector and deregulate financial markets.
</P>
<P>
Geithner, who last week returned from a brief visit to Japan,
said it was unclear whether the political upheaval in Japan
would help to push the reform process ahead.
</P>
<P>
"It's hard to say at this stage what the prospects will be,"
he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
